{After seeing this game I was curious to check my lines in my old notebook and
found the next instructive example on the same theme:} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3.
Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5 7. Bc4 Bg7 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. Be3 O-O 10.
O-O Na5 11. Bd3 b6 12. Qd2 Bb7 13. Bh6 cxd4 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. cxd4 e6 16. Rac1
Qd7 17. h4 Rac8 18. h5 Rxc1 19. Rxc1 Rc8 20. h6+ Kg8 21. Rxc8+ Qxc8 22. Qg5 Qf8
23. Nf4 f6 24. Qg4 Bc8 {So far play has been similar with that from the
previous game, with the difference that White has delayed e4-e5. But now the
right time had come for it already:} 25. e5 $1 ({Vladimirov considers} 25. Nxg6
$1 {insufficient due to} hxg6 26. Qxg6+ Kh8 27. e5 f5 {but he underestimated
White's attacking resources. You will find this position in the test section.
***How to continue the attack with white?}) (25. Nxe6 {is relatively harmless
since after} Qxh6 {Black can start checking.}) 25... Qxh6 {Desperation.} (25...
fxe5 $2 26. Nxg6 {mates while if}) (25... f5 26. Qg5 {the threat d4-d5
followed by e5-e6 is killing. the only way to parry it is} Nc6 {but the
hanging knight offers White such a tactial possibility:} 27. Nxg6 hxg6 28.
Qxg6+ Kh8 29. Bxf5 $1 exf5 30. Qxc6 {The connected passed pawns combined with
the permanent danger on g7 make Black's position hopeless.}) 26. exf6 Kf7 27.
Ba6 $1 (27. d5 $2 {is premature due to} exd5 28. Qxc8 Qxf4 $11 {(Vladimirov)})
27... Bd7 28. d5 {and White won.} 1-0

