{In the previous games, Black's bishop turned being a bad one despite the
optically spectacular activity along the h1-a8 diagonal. But Black's task is
not easier if he exchanges this bishop for a knight, especially if he cannot
transfer his own knight to d5 at once. Here is an illustrative example.} 1. d4
Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Be3 c5 8. Qd2
cxd4 9. cxd4 Nc6 10. Rd1 O-O 11. Nf3 Bg4 12. Be2 Rc8 13. O-O Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Na5
15. Bg5 b6 16. e5 Qd7 17. Rfe1 Nc4 18. Qe2 e6 19. h4 $1 {The familiar signal
to the kingside attack.} ({Unblocking the centre yields very little after} 19.
d5 Nxe5 20. dxe6 Qxe6 21. Bd5 Qf5) 19... h6 {Black usually faces a difficult
choice of principle about how to meet the advance of the h-pawn.} ({Ignoring
the kingside plan is not without dangers:} 19... b5 20. h5 Rfe8 21. hxg6 ({
The most principled continuation even though the central break makes some
sense, too under the changed circumstances:} 21. d5 Nxe5 22. h6 Bh8 23. dxe6
Qxe6 24. Bd5 {The main difference with respect to the similar line above is
that Black should be aware of the potential pin along the e-file as, for
instance, after} Qf5 $6 25. f4) 21... hxg6 22. g3 $1 {A typical way of
activating the rook along the h-file.} Nb6 23. Kg2 Nd5 24. Qe4 {followed by
Rh1 and Qh4 with a decisive attack.}) ({Black's kingside fortress does not
seem too reliable after} 19... h5 20. g4 {either, for instance} hxg4 21. Bxg4
b5 22. h5) 20. Bc1 b5 {The plan of transferring the knight to d5 is time
consuming but there was little Black could do anyway.} 21. h5 g5 {Black has
maintained his kingside stability, but the weakening of the b1-h7 diagonal
will soon tell.} 22. Be4 $1 {Preparing to set up the Bd3 + Qe4 battery against
the black king.} Nb6 23. Bd3 Nd5 ({This loses a pawn but after} 23... a6 24.
Qe4 f5 25. exf6 Bxf6 {Black's position is joyless. The most elegant and
probably strongest continuation is} 26. Be2 $1 {followed by Bg4}) 24. Bxb5 ({
Here, too,} 24. Qe4 {would have been strong but there is no reason for
rejecting the offered pawn.}) 24... Qe7 25. Bd2 f5 26. exf6 Rxf6 27. Bc4 {
and White had little trouble converting his material and positional advantage.}
1-0

