{The Gruenfeld fans can now take a deep breath: the worst is over! We will now
switch to situations when Black can make full use of the weaknesses induced by
e4-e5. ***We will start with two classical examples.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3
d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4 c5 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. Be3 O-O 10. O-O
Qc7 11. Rc1 Rd8 12. Qd2 Qa5 13. Qb2 b6 14. Bd5 Bb7 15. Rfd1 e6 16. Bb3 cxd4 17.
cxd4 Rac8 {Black is perfectly regrouped and so far has managed to keep White's
centre under control. White is doing quite OK, but Gligoric suddenly loses
patiente.} 18. e5 $6 {Since White cannot set up the Qd2 + Be3 battery along
the c1-h6 diagonal, this does not offer realistic attacking chances. Any
half-waiting move such as 18.h3 would have been preferable.} Bf8 {Freed of any
dangers along the long diagonal, Black hurries to re-activate his bishop. The
threats Ba3 and Qa3, ensuring the control over the c-file practically force
White weakening his queenside.} 19. a4 Qb4 {[%cal Gb4a3,Gc6a5] Renewing the
threat Qa3 and creating a new one: Na5.} 20. Qa2 $5 Qe7 $3 {A very elegant and
effective retreat. Black not only removes the queen from an expsed position,
but also dfeends e6 and clears the b4-square for the knight's transfer to d5.
***White's previous move had set up a series of traps:} (20... Ne7 $2 {loses
the queen to} 21. Bd2 $18) (20... Qa3 {allows} 21. Bxe6 fxe6 22. Qxe6+ Kh8 23.
Bg5 {with a strong attack.} Be7 ({Had Black played 20...Na5 instead of 20.Qa3
in this line, he would could have forced a draw by perpetual with} 23... Re8
24. Bf6+ Bg7 {25.Bxg7+ Kxg7 26.Qf6+. But in this line White can win the
undefended b7-bishop with} 25. Qf7 Bxf6 26. exf6 $18) 24. Bxe7 Qxe7 25. Rxc6 {
retrieving the material with interest.}) 21. Nf4 {Anticipating the manoeuvre
Nb4-d5, but Black's knight has an alternate route available.} Na5 $1 22. Rxc8
Rxc8 23. Bc2 Qa3 24. Qb1 {Exchanging queens would bring White closer to a
unpleasant ending.} Qb4 25. h4 {This is more of a prophylactic than an
attacking move. White simply avoids back rank problems.} ({If} 25. Qa2 {
Black can force the queen exchange with} Qc4 26. Qxc4 Rxc4 27. Rd2 Bc6 {
winning the a4-pawn.}) 25... Nc4 26. Bc1 Na3 27. Qxb4 Bxb4 28. Bb3 Nc4 {
Black has invaded the weakened queenside and has strong initiative. The
immediate threat (highlighted by Tukmakov) is 29...Na5 30.Ba2 Bc6 31.Nxe6 Bxa4.
} 29. d5 $5 exd5 30. Nxd5 $2 {This unexpectedly loses material.} ({Tukmakov
recommends} 30. Ba2 {which, indeed, offers White some saving chances in an
ending with a pawn down after} Nxe5 31. Nxd5) 30... Bxd5 31. Rxd5 {You are
kindly invited to find the winning move in the test section.Black to move and
win.} 0-1

