{Under certain circumstances, it makes sense provoking e4-e5 with the resolute
...f7-f5.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7.
Bc4 c5 8. Ne2 O-O 9. O-O Nc6 10. Be3 Qc7 11. Rc1 Rd8 12. h3 b6 13. f4 e6 14.
Qe1 Bb7 15. Qf2 Na5 16. Bd3 {White's previous play has aimed at creating
attacing chances with f4-f5. Smyslow immediately takes preventive measures:} f5
$5 ({On short term, Black could have prevented the start of the attack with} 
16... Qe7 {since} 17. f5 $2 exf5 18. exf5 Re8 19. Bd2 c4 {wins a piece. But on
long term, he would most probably have had to play ...f7-f5 anyway.}) 17. e5 ({
White cannot maintain the tension with} 17. Ng3 {since after} Qd7 $17 {he
would lose the d4-pawn.}) 17... c4 {Ensuring the d5-square for his minor
pieces and preparing the queenside majority attack. ***There are two main
elements making the structure favourable for Black. First of all, there is no
way White could create a strong passed pawn with d4-d5. He would at least need
transferring his light-squared bishop to f3 and the knight to e3. This not
only looks impossible to carry out due to the huge amount of time needed, but
it would not necessarily ensure the success of the break either. ***Secondly,
the f4-pawn restricts White's attacking possibilities, typically based on Qg3,
h2-h4, Bg5 and Nf4.} 18. Bc2 Nc6 19. g4 {The only way to display some activity,
but in the long run the weakness of the long diagonal will be decisive.} Ne7
20. Kh2 Qc6 21. Ng3 b5 22. a4 a6 23. Rb1 Rab8 24. Bd2 bxa4 $5 {This apparent
strategic concession speaks about Black's intentions to play for a win. With
White's actual regrouping, breaking with ...b5-b4 looks improbable so the only
chance remains opening a queenside file.} 25. Ra1 Ba8 26. Bxa4 Qc7 27. Ra2 Rb6
28. gxf5 exf5 $1 ({Another paradoxcial pawn capture away from the centre. It
is essential to keep the g3-knight passive.} 28... gxf5 $6 29. Nh5 {would
suddenly offer White some initiative. As revealed by the game course, White's
central connected passed pawns are not dangerous.}) 29. Bc1 Nd5 30. Ne2 a5 31.
Bc2 {Time has come to invite you spotting Smyslow's secret plan when giving up
the queenside tension (check the test section).How to increase the queenside
pressure with Black?} 0-1

