{In the introduction I have mentioned that Black sometimes has tactical ways
of dismantling White's solid centre, thus activating his g7-bishop. Here is
such a game featuring this idea, played between a famous veteran against a
much younger opponent.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6.
bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4 c5 8. Ne2 O-O 9. O-O Nc6 10. Be3 Bd7 11. Rb1 Rc8 12. Qd2 e6 13.
Rfd1 Na5 14. Bd3 Ba4 15. Rdc1 Qd7 {White's major pieces are dominated by the
light-squared bishop and partly by the knight. But there was no need for
Naumkin's positional concession on the next move.} 16. e5 $6 {This only
weakens the light squares without generating realistic attacking chances.} Nc6
17. Be4 b6 18. h4 Rfd8 {Black completes his development taking measures
against White's planned attack. 19.Bh6 and 19.h5 can both be answred with 19...
Bxe5 or 19...Nxe5, when the absence of a white rook on d1 can be felt. Or if
19.Rb2, over-defending the queen, 19...Na5 would be annoying. Please compare
the knight's balance around the a5-square with the same issue from
Gligoric-Tukmakov above.} 19. Bg5 {Naumkin obviously hoped to force 19...Re8
in order to proceed with his plan, but Kortschnoj had other thoughts.} Nxe5 $1
{A strong positional exchange sacrifice, dissolving White's centre and leaving
the enemy pieces poorly coordinated.} 20. Bxd8 Rxd8 21. Qf4 Nc4 {The errant
knight has finally reached a dream square.} 22. h5 ({Or if} 22. dxc5 e5 $1 {
the queen does not have good squares due to the threat 23...Nd2.}) 22... e5 $1
{Very youthful and consequent play. The opening of the centre strenghenes
Black's initiative since White cannot make use of the d-file.} 23. dxe5 Bxe5
24. Qh4 Nd2 25. Ra1 ({Avoiding} 25. Rb2 $2 Nxe4 26. Qxe4 Qd1+ {mating.}) 25...
Re8 {Things start looking ugly for White but the next move should have led to
immediate defeat.} 26. Bc2 $6 Bb5 $6 {This hesitating move allowed Naumkin
struggling for several dozens of moves.} ({Strong experienced players
sometimes overlook simple possibilities:} 26... Bxc2 $1 27. Rxc2 Qd3 {with a
decisive double attack.} 28. Qa4 {Obviously the only move.} Re6 (28... b5 {
also wins, even though it looks as if Black unnecessarily gives away a pawn:}
29. Rxd2 Qxd2 30. Qxb5 Rb8 {followed by 31...Rb2.}) 29. Ng3 Bxg3 30. fxg3 Re2 {
With the decisive threat 31...Qd5.}) 0-1

