{White in his turn should be carefull maintaining the integrity of his centre.
Symptomatically, even strong players sometimes leave themselves led astray by
the temptation of creating a black weakness after dxc5, ...bxc5, or getting
some dynamic chances after the opening of the d-file, forgetting that this
mainly endangers the e5-pawn. Here are two more games from Kortschnoj's
practice, played at almost three decades distance in time.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6
3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. O-O Qd7
10. Ba3 $6 Na5 11. Bd3 b6 12. Nf4 Bb7 13. Qe2 Rfd8 14. Rad1 e6 {Even though
Black has delayed pawn action in the centre, White's pawn mass is not easy to
put into motion.} 15. e5 $6 {After having examined the previous examples it is
easy to spot that this is premature.} c5 $1 {Black had no reasons to refrain
from this standard move anymore. The immediate positional threat is ...cxd4
followed by Qa4, but Lilienthal had some dynamic ambitions.} 16. dxc5 {
Apparently White wins material. You are invited to prove this wrong in the
test section.How could Black make use of the weakening of the e5-pawn?} 0-1

