{Here is the modern interpretation of the same theme:} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nf3 b6 {I admit this is not a proper Gruenfeld Defence, but it will soon
transpose to positions of the same character.} 4. Nc3 Bb7 5. a3 d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5
7. e3 g6 $5 8. Bb5+ c6 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. e4 Nxc3 11. bxc3 c5 12. Bg5 {True to his
style, the then young World title candidate strives for initiative as soon as
possible. The cunning veteran's next two moves will provoke White's already
familiar positional concessions.} Qd6 13. e5 Qd7 14. dxc5 $6 {In My Great
Predecessors V, Kasparov quotes Kortschnoj: "This move is hard to understand."}
O-O $1 ({Having his memories from the game with Lilienthal, Kortschnoj must
have played this strong move without hesitation. The e5-pawn is doomed while
the queenside structure will favour Black. Kasparov obviously hoped for} 14...
bxc5 $6 15. Bb5 {forcing Black exchanging the bishops and thus releasing the
pressure on e5. For instance} Bc6 16. Bxc6 Nxc6 17. Qxd7+ Kxd7 18. O-O-O+ Kc8
19. Bf6 {with pleasant play for White.}) 15. cxb6 axb6 16. O-O Qc7 $1 {The
best way to start undermining the e5-pawn. Black threatens Nd7 followed by
Nxe5. He could also consider ...Ra5 on the way.} (16... Nc6 {allows White
keeping his extra pawn after} 17. Be4 Qc7 18. Bf6 $1 Bxf6 19. exf6 Qf4 20. Bxc6
Bxc6 21. Qd4 $14) 17. Bb5 $5 {Apparently a principled move, dominating Black's
knight.} ({If} 17. Re1 {Kasparov gives} Nd7 $1 (17... Nc6 {allows} 18. Bf6) 18.
Be7 Bxf3 $1 19. gxf3 Bxe5 20. Bxf8 Rxf8 $15 {with more than enough
compensation for the exchange due to White's ruined structure all over the
board. There is a hidden drawback of White's last move though. Try yourself
with this position in the test section.}) 0-1

