{How to increase the queenside pressure with Black?} 31... Rb3 $1 {This is
reminiscent of Black's Re7-e6 in the famous game Reshevsky-Petrosian, Zurich
1953.} 32. Bxb3 ({This increases Black's domination on light squares but there
was no simple way to defend the c3-pawn:} 32. Bd2 Rdb8 33. Rfa1 Rb2 {with
initiative or}) (32. Qg3 Nb4) 32... cxb3 33. Ra4 Bf8 {A familiar pattern. The
bishop had nothing to do on the long diagonal.} ({The greedy} 33... Nxc3 $6 {
allows White solving his strategic problems:} 34. Nxc3 Qxc3 35. Bb2 Qc7 36. Rc1
Qb6 37. Rc5) ({But activating the other bishop with} 33... Bc6 {was an
important alternative, for instance:} 34. Ra3 a4 35. c4 Nb4 {threatening Nc2
and Nd3. The advance of the massive centre would only weaken pawns and
diagonals:} 36. d5 $6 Bd7 37. e6 $6 Be8 {threatening both Qxc4 and ...b3-b2.})
34. Bb2 ({This allows a tactical trick but the more cautious} 34. Ra1 {would
not spare White problems:} Rb8 35. Bb2 Nb6 36. Rxa5 Nc4) 34... Ne3 $1 35. Rfa1
(35. Qxe3 Qc6 {Attacking the rook and threatening Qg2 mate.} 36. d5 $5 Rxd5 37.
Raa1 Rd2 $1 $19) 35... Nc4 36. Ng3 (36. Rxc4 Qxc4 37. Rxa5 Be7 {followed by ...
Bh4 is lethal.}) 36... Be7 37. Nf1 ({If} 37. Nxf5 gxf5 38. Qg3+ {Black
neutralizes the counterattack with} Kf8 $1 39. Rg1 Bd5 $19 {(Smyslow)}) 37...
Qc6 38. Rxc4 Qh1+ $1 39. Kg3 h5 {0-1 (39) Gligoric,S-Smyslov,V Kiev 1959} (
39... h5 {There is no satisfactory defence against 40...h4 mate, for instance:}
40. Qh2 Qf3#) (39... h5 40. Qe3 Qg2#) (39... h5 40. Qe2 Qg1+ {Therefore,
Gligoric resigned.}) *

