{How could Black make use of the weakening of the e5-pawn?} 16... Qc7 $1 ({
This typical move highlights the drawbacks of White's positional concession.
White cannot save his e5-pawn.} 16... bxc5 {is wrong for at least two reasons:}
17. Bxg6 ({The simple} 17. Bxc5 {is also good, leaving Black with problems
proving his compensation for the pawn.}) 17... Qa4 {Hoping to get some profit
from White's hanging minor pieces.} 18. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 19. Qh5+ Kg8 20. Rxd8+
Rxd8 21. Nxe6 {with overwhelming initiative for the sacrificed piece.}) ({
Other squares than c7 are less favourable for the queen. For instance} 16...
Qe7 17. Be4 {allows White stabilizing the position, leaving the g7-bishop
passive and the black queenside weak.}) 17. cxb6 ({An old commentary suggests} 
17. Rfe1 {as an improvement, but Black can insist with attacking the central
pawn:} Nc6 18. cxb6 Qxe5 $1 ({An important intermediate move. If} 18... axb6
19. Bd6 $14 {White consolidates.}) 19. Qxe5 Bxe5 {with similar play as in the
game.}) ({With the queen on c7} 17. Be4 {does not work so well:} Qxe5 18. Bxb7
Nxb7 19. Qxe5 Bxe5 20. Nd3 Bf6 {and once again Black retains the better
structure.}) 17... Qxe5 $1 18. Qxe5 Bxe5 {It appears that the white knight is
not only passive but also vulnerable. To make things worse, the d3-square is
not available.} 19. Ne2 axb6 20. Bc1 Bd5 $17 {Black has emerged out of the
complications with the better structure and Kortschnoj went on winning
confidently. 0-1 (20) Lilienthal,A-Kortschnoj,V Kiev 1954} *

