{How Black should continue?} 17... Bxe5 $1 {Black retrieves the pawn using the
hanging position of White's bishops. '!?' Apparently a principled move,
dominating Black's knight.} (17... Nc6 {allows White getting close to equality
with} 18. Qd6 Bxe5 19. Qxc7 Bxc7 20. Rfd1 {(Kasparov).}) 18. Bh6 ({As pointed
out by Kasparov,} 18. Nxe5 Qxe5 19. Bh6 {fails to} Qxb5 20. Qd4 e5 $17) 18...
Bg7 $6 {After this passive retreat White could have obtained enough
compensation for his shattered structure.} (18... Rd8 $1 {was better, for
instance:} 19. Nxe5 $5 ({White does not get enough compensation for the queen,
but} 19. Qe2 Bf6 {is not too rosy, either.}) 19... Rxd1 20. Raxd1 {Kasparov
examines several continuations, but I find} Ba6 {strongest. After the forced
exchange of the light-squared bishops White does not have any attacking
chances left.}) 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Qd4+ Kg8 21. Ng5 $2 ({Missing his chance:} 
21. Ne5 Rd8 22. Qh4 {followed by Ng4 with dynamic compensation for the
structural defects. (Kasparov)}) 21... h6 $1 22. Ne4 Bxe4 23. Qxe4 Na6 {
Black has completed his development retaining the better structure.} 24. Qe3 $6
{It is obviously unwise to leave Black with a knight on board.} ({After} 24.
Bxa6 Rxa6 {the maximum Black could hope for would have been a drawn rook
ending with four pawns versus three on the same wing.}) 24... Qc5 $1 25. Qxc5
Nxc5 {Black's knight is obviously stronger than the bishop, adding to the
better structure. Kortschnoj went on winning an instructive ending. 0-1 (25)
Kasparov, G (2690)-Kortschnoj,V (2610) London 1983} *

