{A fascinating game played under the slogan "Everything for the passed pawn!"
Indeed, Kasparov sacrificed the c3-pawn and the g5 bishop on the way, while in
a comment he showed himself ready to have offered Black a choice of which
minor piece to grab! We will now exemplify the opposite situation when the
passed pawn is more of a weakness than strenght. And we will have Kasparov on
the black side, of course.} 1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. d4
Nxc3 6. bxc3 g6 7. e4 Bg7 8. Be3 Qa5 9. Qd2 Bg4 10. Rc1 Bxf3 11. gxf3 e6 {
Diagram [#]} 12. d5 $2 {It will soon turn out that White's bishops will not
have enough activity to sustain the pawns advance, so the last move remains
only a unnecessary weakening of the dark squares. The main problem is created
by the double pawns, standing in the light=squared bishop's way. If White
plays f3-f4, the other bishop would remain passive.} exd5 13. exd5 Nd7 14. c4
Qb6 15. Bh3 f5 $1 {Turning this bishop into a spectator for a long time.} 16.
O-O Qd6 {The queen is known for not being a good blockading piece, but in this
game it will temporarily fulfil this task without problems.} 17. Bf4 Be5 18.
Rfe1 O-O-O $1 {Anticipating the queenside king's activity in the endgame.} 19.
Bxe5 Nxe5 20. Qc3 Rhe8 21. Re3 Qf6 22. f4 ({Only not} 22. Rce1 $4 Nxf3+ $1)
22... Nd7 23. Bg2 Qxc3 24. Rcxc3 Nf6 25. Bf3 Rxe3 26. fxe3 {Diagram [#] White
has improved his pawn structure but this doesn't help him very much as the
black knight is much stronger than the white bishop anyway. Besides, the a2,
c4 and e3 pawns are still weak and (last but not least) the black king is
closer to the battlefield than his white counterpart.} Rd6 $3 {A fantastic
decision! Before installing the knight on d6 Black makes full use of this
square. The rook is heading for a4, in order to put pressure on White's weak
pawns.} (26... Ne8 {The natural} 27. h4 Nd6 {would allow White consolidating
since the black rook would not have active perspectives.} 28. Kf1 a6 29. Ke2
Kd7 30. a4 $11) 27. Ra3 Kb8 {Diagram [#]} 28. Rb3 $6 {Preventing an intrusion
along the b-file but allowing Black to carry out his initial plan.} ({The
regrouping starting with} 28. Ra5 {would have offered better chances for
defending this inferior ending:} Nd7 29. Bd1 Rb6 30. Bb3 Rb4 31. Kf1 b6 32. Ra4
Nf6 33. Ke2 a5 34. Kd3 Kc7 $15 {White's position remains unpleasant but as
long as he avoids clearing the c5-square with Rxb4, ...axb4, he is not in
immediate danger of losing.}) 28... Ra6 29. a3 Ne8 $1 {The long awaited moment
when the knight is transferred to d6.} 30. e4 {It's now or never. White
probably hoped to attack the kingside pawns with his bishop, but this will
happen too late to save the game.} fxe4 31. Bxe4 Nd6 32. Bd3 Ra4 33. Rc3 Kc7
34. Kf2 {Diagram [#] Black has completed his regrouping and time has come for
the thematical pawn break:} b5 $1 $17 35. cxb5 Kb6 36. Ke3 c4 37. Bc2 Nxb5 $1 {
Small tactical fireworks are typical for the technical phase in the endgame.}
38. Bxa4 Nxc3 {Diagram [#] Things have partly cleared up. Black will finally
win the d5-pawn, which had imprudently advanced 26 moves earlier. The only
open problem remains whether White will manage activating his king in order to
save the game.} 39. Be8 {This will allow Black staying in control with the
help of a small tactical trick a few moves later.} ({But the same applies to} 
39. Bc2 {:} Kc5 40. d6 $5 Kxd6 41. f5 ({The problem is that} 41. Kd4 {runs into
} Nb5+ 42. Kxc4 Nxa3+ {Compare with the next line.}) 41... g5 42. f6 h5 $17 {
The f-pawn is inoffensive leaving White short of adequate ways to keep the
c-pawn and the kingside majority under control.}) 39... Kc5 40. d6 Nd5+ $1 {
The best way of keeping the enemy king under control.} 41. Ke4 Nf6+ 42. Ke3 ({
Sad necessity since} 42. Ke5 Nxe8 43. d7 {is refuted by} Nd6 {forcing} 44. d8=N
c3 45. Ne6+ Kc4 46. Nd4 Nb5 $19) 42... Kxd6 {With the king on e3 the bishop is
taboo, but White now has to spend a tempo, allowing the black king's return in
the centre.} 43. Bf7 Kc5 44. h4 Ng4+ 45. Kd2 ({Another line illustrating the
knight's vitality is} 45. Ke4 Nh6 46. Be6 Nf5 47. h5 Ng3+ $1) 45... Kd4 46. h5
gxh5 47. Bxh5 Nf6 {Feeling helpless against Black's passers, so remote from
each other, White resigned.} 0-1

