{This position arose after 22...Nc4 23.Bxc4 Rxc4 24.h6 Bg7. Try using the
mobile centre and the far advanced h-pawn to prove Black's hopes for queenside
counterplay illusory.} 25. d5 $3 {Everything is ready for this thematic break,
even though the b2-bishop seems to be handing.} ({defending it in advance with
} 25. Qb3 {runs into} Qa4 {with acceptable play for Black.}) 25... Bxb2 26. Qb3
$1 {The point. White retrieves the piece keeping strong initiative in the
centre and dangerous kingside threats.} Rxe4 (26... exd5 27. Qxb2 d4 {runs into
} 28. Ne5 Qa4 29. Nxc4 Qxc4 30. Rd2 {followed by Red1 with a clear extra
exchange.}) ({The counterblow} 26... Bc3 {loses instantly after} 27. dxe6 $18)
27. Qxb2 $1 (27. Rxe4 Bh8 {offers Black ample compensation for the exchange.})
27... Rxe1+ 28. Rxe1 f6 29. Qxf6 $1 (29. Rxe6 $6 {was played in the game.})
29... Bxd5 (29... Rf8 30. dxe6 Qc7 31. Qd4 $18 {is also hopeless.}) 30. Ne5 Qc7
{and now the killing move, possibly overlooked by Podgaets, is} 31. Nf7 $1 $18
{winning the exchange due to the threat Qg7 mate while keeping the initiative.}
1-0

