{Dear reader, Welcome to the third article of our series concerning the
Grunfeld structures. In the previous article, we were dealing with White's
idea to create a central passed pawn by playing d4-d5. We have seen that such
a central pawn has a number of advantages and drawbacks. This time, however,
we are going to examine some situations when White goes for d4-d5 without
creating a passed pawn. As I have pointed out in the previous article, such an
idea could seriously restrict Black's active options.  For once, we will see
Kasparov unable to deal with the critical situation.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3
d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Be3 c5 8. Qd2 O-O 9. Nf3 Bg4 10. Ng5
$5 cxd4 11. cxd4 Nc6 12. h3 Bd7 13. Rb1 Rc8 14. Nf3 Na5 15. Bd3 Be6 16. O-O Bc4
17. Rfd1 {Diagram [#] White has managed keeping his centre intact for a long
time so Black's main source of counterplay is his control over the c4-square.
The next move is aimed to strengthen his outpost but after a later inaccuracy
the weakening of the c6-square will be decisive.} b5 18. Bg5 {The bishop moves
out of the knight's range causing Black some mini-problems with his e7-pawn.}
a6 19. Rbc1 Bxd3 20. Rxc8 Qxc8 21. Qxd3 Re8 $2 {Diagram [#] This is the main
cause for Black's future problems. Many alternatives have been suggested but I
will only mention one which as far as I know have escaped the commentators'
attention, but which is has the tightest connection with our main theme and
the previous examples.} (21... e6 $5 {Now is a good moment to take this type
of measures aganst d4-d5.} 22. d5 ({Unlike in the game,} 22. Rc1 {can be
safely met with} Nc4 {since} 23. Nd2 {runs into} Nb2 $1 {In the similar
position which could have arised after Kasparov's last move the e8-rook would
be hanging.}) 22... Nc4 $1 ({An interesting moment. Inserting} 22... exd5 23.
exd5 {would conceal White the d5-square and the open e-file:} Nc4 24. d6 Qd7 {
He could play} 25. Qe4 $14 {planning Qe7 since} Re8 $2 26. Qxe8+ $1 {wins.})
23. d6 Qd7 {The pawns looks threatening but White's major pieces do not have
enough space to unblock it.} 24. Be7 Rc8 (24... Nb2 $2 25. Qc2 Nxd1 {allows}
26. Bxf8 Bxf8 $6 27. e5 {when the pawn will soon become a problem.}) 25. Rc1
Rc6 26. a4 Bf8 {The final phase of the pawn's siege. The position suddenly
becomes double-edged for instance:} 27. Bxf8 Kxf8 28. axb5 axb5 29. e5 Nxe5 $1)
22. Rc1 Qb7 23. d5 $1 {Diagram [#] After a long phase of subtle maneouvring,
White finally reveals his secret card: the invasion of the c6-square.} Nc4 ({
A few moves later the back rank weakness will play an important part. But} 
23... h6 {would drive the bishop on another active diagonal:} 24. Bf4 $1 Nc4
25. Nd2 {with the idea of} Nxd2 26. Rc7 $1) 24. Nd2 Nxd2 $6 {Diagram [#]} ({
Botvinnik once wrote: if you have weaknesses, try keeping a knight. This
applies here perfectly as} 24... Ne5 {would have offered some chances to keep
the fight double-edged even though the knight is obviously unstable and White
would retain pressure with, say,} 25. Qa3 {Black could strike with} f5 {
preparing the knight's retreat to f7 in case of emergency, and facing White
with some problems converting his strategic advantage.}) 25. Bxd2 $1 Rc8 26.
Rc6 $1 {Diagram [#] Kasparov confesses he had overlooked this simple move
crowning White's previous play.} Be5 {Symptomatically, the bishop was not
doing much on the long diagonal so Kasparov decides using it for queenside
defence.} ({Black needs living with the rook on c6 since} 26... Rxc6 27. dxc6 {
leads to a quick defeat:} Qc7 (27... Qxc6 $2 28. Qd8+ Bf8 29. Bh6 {mates.}) 28.
Qd7 Be5 29. Bb4 {Busy with blocking the far advanced pawn, Black is helpless
against the simple kingside threats (for instance Bxe7, Qe8-f8 mate)}) 27. Bc3
Bb8 ({The queen ending after} 27... Bxc3 28. Qxc3 Rxc6 29. dxc6 {is hopeless
in the long run since the pawn paralyzes Black.}) 28. Qd4 f6 29. Ba5 {White is
in complete control of the position and won eleven moves later.} 1-0

