1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Be3 c5 8.
Qd2 Qa5 9. Rb1 b6 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Be2 Bc6 12. Bd3 Nd7 13. Ne2 {Diagram [#]
White has chosen a contorted way of developing, aimed at preventing the knight
from reaching c6.} Rd8 $1 {At that time a novelty, not only anticipating d4-d5
but also creating the potential threat Nd7-e5.} 14. f3 O-O 15. h4 h5 16. Bg5
Rfe8 17. Rc1 {White keeps wasting time while Black is fully mobilized already.}
Bb7 $1 {Diagram [#] A subtle move yielding Black's position perfect harmony.
The bishop steps out of the d-pawn's range while keeping the possibility of
switching to the f1-a6 diagonal.} 18. d5 $2 ({This is one of the least
favorable situations for this thematic advance. True, natural moves would not
spare White problems already:} 18. O-O Ne5 $1 19. Bb1 (19. dxe5 {runs into} c4
{retrieving the piece and retaining the bishops pair and the better structure.}
) 19... Ba6) 18... Ne5 {The first moment when a black minor piece uses the
concealed e5-square. The immediate threat is ...Rd7 followed by ...e7-e6,
winning the d5-pawn.} 19. Bb1 {Abandoning the control of the c4-square looks
strange, but White hoped to consolidate his centre with c3-c4.} (19. c4 $2 {
is impossible due to} Nxd3+) ({or if} 19. O-O Rd7 20. c4 Qxd2 21. Bxd2 Nxd3 {
winning the bishop in both cases.}) 19... Nc4 20. Qf4 $4 {Diagram [#] "In bad
positions all moves are bad" (Tarrasch) True, but this is the worst thinkable
of!} ({True, White's position would be critical after other retreats, too, for
instance:} 20. Qd1 e6 $5 21. Bxd8 Rxd8 {winning the central pawn with
overwhelming initiative for the exchange or}) (20. Qd3 Ba6 21. O-O Rd7 ({
Even stronger than} 21... Na3 22. Qd2 Nxb1 23. Rxb1 Bxe2 24. Qxe2 Qxc3 $17 {
winning a less important pawn than the central one.}) 22. Rfe1 e6 $19) 20...
Be5 {The second piece lands on this square trapping the queen.} 0-1

