{Diagram [#] White has prematurely played d4-d5 but in order to punish him
Black needs finding the best way of defending the c-pawn.} 12... c4 $1 ({
In the game Black played} 12... Nd7 $6 {allowing White strengthening his
centre with} 13. c4 {, leading to unclear play.}) 13. Rb4 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Qa3 {
This is one of those cases when White cannot ignore the threat on c3.} 15. Bd4
Bxd4 16. Qxd4 (16. cxd4 $2 {strengthens the centre but... loses a rook to} c3
$1) 16... O-O 17. Qd2 {A necessary waste of time since a2 was hanging. ***Over
the previous phase, Black has won a developing tempo (castling). Now is a good
moment to break the centre.} e6 $1 18. dxe6 {Otherwise the pawn would be
doomed, for instance:} (18. d6 Nc6 19. Rb1 Ne5 20. Be2 Rad8 {or}) (18. Be2 exd5
19. exd5 Rd8 20. O-O Nc6 {followed by ...Ne7.}) 18... Nc6 $1 {Diagram [#]} ({
There is nothing wrong with} 18... fxe6 $17 {clearing the f-file for attacking
White's chronic weaknesses, but developing is the highest priority.}) 19. e7 ({
In vain trying to slow down Black's initiative, but} 19. exf7+ Rxf7 20. Rb1 Rd8
{is also hopeless.}) 19... Rfe8 20. Rb1 Ne5 21. Be2 Rxe7 {Black will soon
occupy the d-file and invade the d3-square with his knight. Instead of any
shadow of counterplay, White has only weaknesses on the other wing.} 1/2-1/2

