{Diagram [#] White's d-pawn looks strong but his coordination is imperfect as
some of his pieces stand in eachother's way. Black rightly initiated his
queenside counterplay:} 22... b5 23. axb5 Na3 24. Rd1 {The question is how to
proceed now in order to keep the d5-pawn under control and the c3-pawn under
pressure.} c4 $1 ({This is much stronger than Timman's natural} 24... axb5 $6 {
leading to unclear play after} 25. d6 Nc4 26. Ng3 Qc6 27. Ne4 h6 28. g4 $1 {
Black's position is doubtlessly harmonious but White has also improved his
coordination while his d-pawn is well defended.}) 25. Qd2 Nxb5 $1 {Diagram [#]
The point of the previous move. The knight not inhibits the d-pawn's advance
but also puts pressure on c3, tying up his white colleague to its defence.} 26.
Bh6 {The best chance, reducing the pressure on c3.} ({A neutral move such as} 
26. Rff1 {is answered with} Ra7 {[%cal Ga7d7] followed by ...Rad7.}) (26. d6 $2
{simply does not work:} Nxd6 $1 27. Bxd6 Bf8 {winning a pawn for nothing.})
26... Bxh6 27. Qxh6 Qc5 {Black immediately invades the black squares which
were weakened after the bishops exchange.} 28. Qd2 Rd6 29. Ng3 {Forcing the
slight weakening of Black's kingside.} (29. Nf4 a5 $1 {reveals another merit
of placing the knight on b5: the pawn will be absolutely safe on a3.}) 29... f5
30. Ne2 Re8 31. Nf4 ({There is no time for preparing Nf4 with all the comfort
by playing} 31. h4 {due to} Re3 {attacking c3.}) 31... g5 $1 32. Ne2 (32. Nh3
Re3 33. Nxg5 Nxc3 {offers Black a winning initiative.}) 32... h6 $17 {Unlike
in the game, White is as poorly coordinated as in the test position while
Black clearly dominates the centre.} 0-1

