{As we know already, d4-d5 frequently implies sacrificing some material. In
the last example we will examine a slightly unusual situation: White advanced
his pawn without investing material but several moves later had to sacrifice a
pawn in order to neutralize Black's counterplay.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7
4. Nc3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 8. Be3 Qa5 9. Qd2 O-O 10. Rc1 cxd4
11. cxd4 Qxd2+ 12. Nxd2 Nc6 13. d5 Nb4 14. Bc4 {Diagram [#] Black's knight
faces the perspective of landing on the passive a6-square so he tried to make
use of the available diagonal to include his bishop into play:} Bb2 15. Rb1
Nc2+ 16. Ke2 Nxe3 17. Rxb2 $3 ({A great move, sacrificing the g2-pawn, but not
a difficult to decide upon since after} 17. Kxe3 Ba3 {only Black can be better
due to his bishops pair.}) 17... Nxg2 18. Kf3 ({Improving over} 18. Rc1 {
as played in Portisch-Adorjan, Hungary 1981. ***Ehlvest's idea was getting the
maximum out of the errant knight's misplacing.}) 18... Nh4+ 19. Kg3 g5 20. f4
h6 21. Nf3 $1 {Diagram [#] After reaching his first goals (gaining space and
weakening Black's kingside) White exchanges the knight which was threatening
to set up a blockade with ...Ng6.} Nxf3 22. Kxf3 b6 $6 {Black chooses his
priorities wrongly. Developing is important but the king's safety even more.} (
{True,} 22... Kh8 {does not solve all problems:} 23. fxg5 hxg5 24. h4 g4+ 25.
Kf4 {As we will see, Black's material advantage is temporary.} b6 26. Rc1 Bb7
27. Bb3 Rac8 28. Rbc2 Rxc2 29. Rxc2 Rc8 30. Rxc8+ Bxc8 31. e5 Bd7 32. Bd1 {
retrieving the pawn with excellent winning chances.}) (22... Kg7 23. Rg1 f6 {
is relatively best even though White keeps excellent compensation with, say}
24. Rc1 {.}) 23. Rg1 Bb7 24. fxg5 Rac8 25. Bb3 Rc3+ 26. Kf4 Kh7 27. gxh6 Kxh6
28. Rbg2 {Diagram [#] This is the worst situation for Black. The material is
equal, his king unsafe and the white centre threatening.} Ba6 29. Rg3 Rxg3 30.
Rxg3 f6 31. Bd1 Bc4 32. Kf5 Rc8 33. Bb3 b5 34. Bxc4 $6 (34. e5 $1 {planning to
meet} fxe5 {with} 35. Rg6+ Kh7 36. Rc6 $16) ({or} 34. Ke6 Rc7 35. Rg8 $16 {
are more accurate.}) 34... bxc4 35. Rc3 Rc7 36. a4 Kg7 37. e5 fxe5 38. Kxe5 Rc8
39. Ke6 Rc7 40. a5 {I assume that Black lost on time since resigning surely
looks premature.} 1-0

