1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 O-O 7. O-O c5 8. e4
Nb6 9. d5 Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 N8d7 12. Qe2 c4 13. Nc3 Nc5 14. Be3 Nd3 15.
Rab1 Nd7 16. f4 Rc8 17. e5 {Diagram [#] As usual, a strong centre is more
threatening if sustained by the bishop's pair. Even though the e4- and
d4-squares are emtpy, they are firmly controlled by White. To complete the
picture, the situation os all Black's minor pieces is precarious. The
seemingly active d3-knight is in fact vulnerable due to the threat b2-b3 while
his colleague cannot find a good square easily.} N7c5 {If Black could arrange
playing ...b7-b5-b4 he would have good counterplay but there simply is no time
for that.} 18. b4 $1 {Putting an end to Black's queenside ambitions.} cxb3 ({
Principled but not satisfactory.} 18... Na6 {allows White consolidating with}
19. a3 {and after} b6 {, defending a7,} 20. h4 {would start a slow but in the
long run decisive kingside attack. After h4-h5 or ...h7-h5 Black could forget
about ...f7-f6 as this would weaken the g6-square.}) 19. axb3 Qa5 {Diagram [#]}
20. Ne4 {Dismantling Black's structure and threatening 21.Nxc5 Nxc5 22.b4.} Qb4
(20... Nxe4 {is no better:} 21. Bxe4 Nb4 (21... Nc5 {loses a pawn to} 22. b4
Qa6 23. Qxa6 Nxa6 24. Bxa7 {without improving Black's position in any way.})
22. Ra1 Qd8 23. Rfd1 $16 {with complete domination.}) 21. Nxc5 Nxc5 22. Kh2 $5
{[%cal Ge3d2] In one-sided positions it makes sense playing prophylactic moves.
White prepares Bd2 followed by b3-b4 with a clear advantage on the whole board,
without needing to worry about ...Qd4+.} f6 {A desperate atempt at counterplay,
resulting into the weakening of the light squares. But the alternatives were
not rosy either.} (22... a5 23. Bd2 Qb6 24. b4 axb4 25. Rxb4 Qc7 26. Be3 {
followed by either Rfb1 or Rd1 and d5-d6.}) (22... Ne4 23. Rfc1 {(Planning 24.
Rc4 Rxc4 25.Qxc4.)} Nc3 24. Qe1 {Threatening Rc2 followed by Rbc1.} Na2 25.
Qxb4 Nxb4 26. Rc4 a5 27. Bb6 {with decisive advantage in both cases.}) 23. d6 {
Not the only good move.} exd6 24. exd6 Ne4 25. d7 Rcd8 26. Qc4+ Qxc4 27. bxc4
f5 28. Bxe4 fxe4 29. Rxb7 Rf6 30. Rd1 {Diagram The rest is simple. White has
two connected pawns and Black has no means of stopping them.} Re6 31. Rxa7 Kf7
({Or if} 31... Rc6 {preventing Rc7,} 32. Rb7 {followed by Bb6 wins.}) 32. Rc7 (
{Here, too,} 32. Rb7 {is good enough.}) 32... Ra6 33. Rc8 Bf6 34. c5 Ra3 35. c6
{This game gave us the complete picture of a crushing white space advantage.
We will now examine another classical game in which the favourable elements
are completely missing.} 1-0

