1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. g3 Bg7 6. Bg2 Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 8.
e3 O-O 9. Ne2 Nd7 10. O-O Rb8 11. e4 b5 12. f4 b4 13. e5 Ba6 14. cxb4 cxb4 15.
Re1 Bc4 16. Be3 Nb6 17. d5 Qd7 18. Qd2 Rfd8 19. Bxb6 Rxb6 20. Red1 Qa4 {
Diagram [#] The presence of only two minor pieces on each side has double
consequences. First of all, White finds it more difficult sustaining his
central pawn and secondly Black has fewer problems of coordination. ***This
time the bishops pair belongs to Black, once again with two important
consequences. The bishop outside the pawn chain is more difficult to restrict
than the d7-knight in the previous game while the g7-bishop is very much alive
in the absence of an opponent. Apart from the permanent threat of ...f7-f6 (or
...e7-e6 and if d5-d6 then ...f7-f6) Black has some tactical ideas as we will
see in the final sequence. ***Finally, Black has a space advantage on the
queenside (as we know he had no time for playing ...b7-b5-b4 in the previous
game). This turns the a2-pawn into a weakness and the queenside majority into
a potential danger in the ending. ***For White the main issue is activating
his knight, which he failed to do in the game.} 21. Qe3 $6 ({Now was the only
moment when jumping ahead would offer chances for saving the game:} 21. Nd4 $1
{White threatens both Nc2-e3 and Nb3, more or less forcing Black's answer.}
Bxd5 22. Nc2 $1 {Pinning the bishop and attacking b4, thus restricting Black's
possibilites.} Rc8 (22... e6 23. Ne3 {should also suffice for a draw.}) 23.
Bxd5 Rxc2 (23... Qxc2 24. Rac1 {offers White strong initiative for the pawn
since the g7-bishop is not playing.}) 24. Bb3 Rxd2 25. Bxa4 {and Black has
every chance to hold this ending with opposite coloured bishops.}) 21... Qa6 $1
{With the queen on e3 the b4-pawn is not hanging anymore so Black can play his
thematic move at once.} 22. Nc1 {Too passive to be good. After Black's
excellent answer both white rooks will be hanging.} ({True, White's position
was not easy for instance} 22. Nd4 Bxd5 23. Nc2 e6 {keeping the extra pawn or})
(22. Bf3 Rbb8 {and White finds it difficult playing a constructive move.})
22... e6 $1 {Winning a pawn due to a double pin system. White didn't notice
one of them, making things only worse.} 23. d6 $2 Rbxd6 $1 {The rest is agony.}
24. exd6 Bxa1 25. Nb3 Bc3 26. Qc5 Be2 27. Bf1 Bxf1 28. Qc7 Bf6 29. d7 Bh3 {
These were two extreme examples, one largely favouring White and the other
very pleasant for Black. Things are not always that clearcut and more
typically the evaluation depends on tiny tactical subtleties as in the next
example.} 0-1

