1. c4 Nf6 2. d4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 dxc4 6. Qa4+ Nfd7 7. Nf3 Nc6 8.
Be3 Nb6 9. Qc2 Bf5 10. Qd2 O-O 11. O-O Qd7 12. Rfd1 Rfd8 13. Rac1 Rab8 14. Qe1
a5 15. Qf1 h6 16. d5 Nb4 17. Bxb6 cxb6 18. Nd4 Qd6 19. a3 Na6 20. e4 Bg4 21. f3
Bd7 22. Qxc4 Rbc8 23. Qe2 Qc5 24. e5 b5 25. f4 b4 26. axb4 axb4 27. Na2 Qa5 28.
Ra1 Nc5 29. Qd2 Na6 30. Qe3 Bg4 31. Re1 {Diagram In the first example, each
side has three minor pieces, but Black's coordination is almost perfect and he
has the bishops pair. On the other hand, instead of a queenside majority he
has double pawns, but Bronstein used to like them a lot, saying that they
implied having an extra open file. In this case, the role of the b4-pawn is
restrticting the a2-knight. And still, if White was given the time to play
h2-h3, forcing ...Bd7, his centre would be absolutely safe, ensuring him a
lasting advantage. This forces Black attacking the d5-pawn at once.} Nc7 $1 32.
Nc3 $6 {When playing this tempting move White missed a few tactical finesses.}
(32. Nb3 Qb5 {does not improve White's position and with his d5-pawn doomed he
would have to fight for equality after:} 33. Bf1 Qd7 ({Slightly better than} 
33... Qxd5 34. Nxb4 Qd7 35. Bg2) 34. Nxb4 Nxd5 35. Nxd5 Qxd5) ({It was
necessary to remove the queen from its vulnerable position and keep Nc3 in
reserve with:} 32. Qf2 $1 Nxd5 $5 ({The crtical continuation since} 32... Qb6
33. h3 Bd7 34. Nb3 Qxf2+ 35. Kxf2 $14 {allows White consolidating.}) 33. Nc3
Qc5 ({The queen sacrifice} 33... Qxa1 34. Rxa1 bxc3 {runs into} 35. h3 $16 {
when due to the hanging d5-knight the bishop has no good squares for
retreating.}) 34. Nxd5 Rxd5 35. Bxd5 Qxd5 36. Nc2 Qb5 {Black does not have
full compensation for the exchange since one of the bishop is passive, but
White's play is by no means easy since he has to permanently worry about the
threats on light squares.}) 32... Qc5 33. Na4 {Diagram [#]} Qa5 $2 {Dooming
Black to a hopeless position.} ({I suppose that both players had calculated} 
33... Nxd5 $1 34. Qf2 (34. Nxc5 Nxe3 $17 {is simply bad for White.}) 34... Qc7
35. h3 {when as in the line involving a queen sacrifice the bishop does not
seem to have good squares. However, after} Bd7 $1 36. Bxd5 {Black has} b5 {
retrieving the piece. White has a few ways of keeping approximate equality but
not more. For instance:} 37. f5 $5 (37. e6 bxa4 38. exd7 $2 Qxd7 {retrieves
the piece with advantage.}) 37... gxf5 38. Nxf5 Bxf5 39. Nb6 Rb8 40. Bxf7+ Kxf7
41. Nd5 $1 ({This is the right move order as} 41. Qxf5+ Kg8 42. Nd5 Qc5+ 43.
Ne3 Rd2 {hands in the initiative to Black.}) 41... Rxd5 42. Qxf5+ Ke8 (42...
Kg8 $2 43. Qe6+ {wins the rook.}) 43. Qg6+ Kd7 44. Qxg7 Qc5+ {Both kings are
exposed and play remains unclear.}) 34. Nb3 $1 {Diagram [#] With the knight on
a4, this is much more effective than in the line indicated in the comments to
the 32nd move.} Qb5 35. Nb6 {This is the point! The d5-pawn is safe and Black
will soon be paralyzed.} Rb8 36. Ra5 Qe8 37. h3 Bd7 38. Rc1 Na8 {Quite a
joyless retreat since taking on b6 is not a threat as revealed soon.} 39. Rca1
h5 40. h4 f6 ({Or if} 40... Nxb6 41. Qxb6 f6 42. e6 Bc8 43. Qc7 {wins material.
}) 41. e6 (41. Nxd7 Rxd7 42. Nc5 {followed by Ne6 is also killing.}) 41... Bb5
42. Qc5 {Diagram [#]} (42. d6 $1 {was much stronger for instance} Nxb6 (42...
exd6 43. e7 {and}) (42... Rxd6 43. Rxa8 {win the cornered knight.}) 43. Qxb6 {
The bishop is hanging so Black has no time to prevent the crushing d6-d7.})
42... Nxb6 43. Qxb6 Bc4 {Black now gets some feeble hopes.} 44. Qxb4 Bxb3 45.
Qxb3 f5 46. Kh2 Bf6 47. Rb5 b6 48. Rb4 Rd6 49. Ra7 Qd8 50. Rc4 b5 51. Rcc7 b4
52. Rc6 Rb6 53. Qc4 Rb8 54. b3 Kg7 55. Rcc7 Kh6 56. Qc5 Qh8 57. Rxe7 Bxe7 58.
Rxe7 Ra6 59. d6 Qc3 60. Qc7 Rh8 61. Qxc3 bxc3 62. d7 {In all the games
examined so far White had a perfect structure (always the same, pawns from h2
to e5 and d5.) If any of this pawns is missing, things become double-edged
strategically as in the next game.} 1-0

