1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4 O-O 8.
Ne2 c5 9. O-O Nc6 10. Be3 Bg4 11. d5 Na5 12. Bd3 c4 13. Bc2 Bxc3 14. Rb1 Bg7
15. f3 Bd7 16. f4 b5 17. e5 a6 18. Nc3 Rb8 19. Ba7 Rb7 20. Bc5 Re8 21. Qf3 Rb8
22. Qf2 Qc8 23. Ba7 Ra8 24. Bb6 Nb7 25. h3 Bf5 26. Ne4 Qd7 27. g4 Bxe4 28. Bxe4
Rac8 29. a4 c3 30. axb5 axb5 31. Rfc1 Bh6 32. g5 Bg7 33. Qe3 h6 34. gxh6 Bxh6
35. Rxc3 Rxc3 36. Qxc3 Rc8 37. Qg3 {[#]White has a strong bishops' pair and
huge space advantage but some of his pawns are vulnerable and his coordination
imperfect.} Rc4 38. Re1 ({The resolute} 38. e6 $6 {only plays in Black's hands:
} Qd6 $1 39. exf7+ Kxf7 {as both bishops are hanging now.}) 38... e6 39. f5 $5
({A thematic pawn break aiming at unblocking the e-pawn. If} 39. d6 {Timman
intended to play} Nxd6 40. exd6 ({Or if} 40. Qd3 Bxf4 41. exd6 Qxd6) 40... Qxd6
41. Bf2 Bxf4 {with a more or less similar balanced position as in the game.})
39... exf5 {[#]} 40. Bg2 ({Polugaevsky might have initially planned} 40. e6 $6
{but once again Black can make good use of the concealed d6-square.} Qd6 $1 41.
Qxd6 Nxd6 42. Bd3 Rc3 43. Bf1 Kf8 {Black's chances are better due to his extra
pawn and the strong blocking knight.}) 40... Bf4 41. Qf2 ({In his comments for
the Chess Informant Timman analyses such a crazy line:} 41. Qa3 $5 b4 42. e6
bxa3 43. exd7 a2 44. d6 {The pawn race is really breathtaking but it looks
like something Timman would gladly go for. I told him that my feeling was that
he knew no fear and always embarked principled lines. He seemed pleased to
hear that and sort of modestly confirmed my view.} Rc1 45. Rxc1 Bxc1 46. Bxb7
Be3+ $1 47. Bxe3 a1=Q+ 48. Kg2 Qb2+ 49. Kg3 Qe5+ {Timman ends his line here
with the evaluation "=" (draw by perpetual). In fact, Black can play on:} 50.
Bf4 Qf6 51. h4 Qd8 52. Bc6 f6 {Black threatens to advance his pawns with the
support of the king and partially of the queen. It is unclear yet if this is
enough for a win, but play is one-sided as Black has no way of attacking the
queen with his dark-squared bishop.}) 41... Qe7 42. d6 {Facing the threat of
losing the e5-pawn Polugaevsky finally advances his d-pawn.} Nxd6 43. exd6 Qxd6
{[#]The material is equal and Black is out of any danger of losing. One
important thing is that if all the pieces with the exception of the
light-squared bishop get off board, White could not win even in the improbable
case of grabbing all the black pawns due to the unfavourable colour of the
h8-square. ***But while still in the middlegame I believe that Black's play is
easier since his king is much better defended. ***Polugaevsky thought
differently and tried starting an attack which will prove wrong.} 44. Re8+ $6
Kh7 45. Rd8 $2 Bh2+ {Suddenly it is Black who's attacking.} 46. Kh1 Rc1+ 47.
Bf1 Rxf1+ 48. Qxf1 Qxb6 49. Rd5 Bc7 $1 {[#]Black has a material advantage
already. His winning plan is combining the advance of the b-pawn with the
kingside threats, so White has to try eliminating that pawn.} 50. Rxb5 (50.
Qxb5 $2 Qf2 {mating is even worse, of course. (Timman)}) 50... Qc6+ 51. Kg1
Bb6+ 52. Kh2 Qc2+ 53. Qg2 ({There is no safe place for the king anymore. For
instance:} 53. Kg3 Bc7+ 54. Kf3 Qe4+ 55. Kf2 Bb6+ $1 56. Kg3 (56. Rxb6 Qd4+ {
with the same type of queen ending as in the game.}) 56... f4+ 57. Kh2 Be3 {
followed by ...f4-f3 with a decisive attack.}) 53... Qc7+ $1 54. Qg3 (54. Kh1
$2 {leads to mate:} Qc1+ 55. Kh2 Bc7+) 54... Bg1+ $1 55. Kg2 Qc6+ 56. Kxg1 Qxb5
{The remaining moves were played by inertia.} 57. Qh4+ Kg7 58. Qd4+ f6 59. Qa7+
Kh6 60. Qf7 Qe5 61. Kg2 f4 62. Qf8+ Kg5 63. Qc8 f3+ 0-1

