{[#]} {With so few pieces White's space advantage actually implies a major
weakening. And still, if he gets playing d5-d6 or e5-e6, the position would be
unclear. How would you strike with Black?} 24... Nc4 $1 {Suddenly both central
pawns are in danger.} 25. Nxc4 (25. d6 exd6 26. e6 {does not offer enough
counterplay as White does not have enough pieces to bring into the attack.}
fxe6 27. Nxc4 Rxc4 28. Qf6 Qf7 $19) ({Or if} 25. e6 Nxe3 26. exf7+ Kxf7 27.
Qxe3 Rxd5 {Black simply wins a pawn.}) 25... Rxc4 26. Qe3 (26. d6 Rxd4 27. dxc7
Rc4 {leads to a joyless rook ending with a pawn down.}) 26... Rc3 {Repeting
the moves before hitting on the right ttrack.} 27. Qd4 ({White cannot escape
the repetition for if} 27. Qe4 Qc5+ 28. Kh1 Rc4 29. Qd3 Rd4 {wins the d5-pawn.}
) 27... Rc4 28. Qe3 Rc2 $1 29. e6 {The best practical chance.} ({If} 29. a4 Qc4
{White does not have time for defending the d5-pawn due to the threat ...Qa2.})
(29. Rf2 Rxf2 30. Kxf2 Qc2+ {once again loses the d5-pawn:} 31. Qe2 (31. Kf1
Qd1+) 31... Qc5+) 29... Qc5 30. Qxc5 Rxc5 31. Rd1 (31. exf7+ Kxf7 32. Rd1 Rc3
33. f4 b5 34. Rd2 b4 {is also promising for Black.}) 31... fxe6 32. dxe6 Ra5
33. Rd2 Kg7 34. f4 Kf6 35. Re2 g5 ({and now the most active plan was} 35... Ra3
36. Kf2 b5 {followed by the massive advance of the queenside pawns with
excellent winning chances.}) 36. fxg5+ Kxg5 37. Kg2 Kf5 38. Kf3 Ra3+ 39. Kg2
Ra5 40. Kh3 Ra4 41. Rb2 Kxe6 42. Rb5 Rxa2 43. Rxh5 Rb2 44. Rh8 a5 45. Kg4 a4
46. Ra8 Rb4+ 47. Kf3 b5 48. h4 Kf6 49. g4 Rb3+ 50. Ke4 a3 51. Ra6+ Kg7 52. Kf5
b4 53. Ra7 Rf3+ 54. Ke4 Rf2 55. Ke3 Rb2 0-1

