{[#]} {Both sides seem having a stable position, but Black found a way of
winning the important d5-pawn. Your move. ***As we see, the Gruenfeld
"existed" long before its official launching in the famous game
Alekhine-Gruenfeld Vienna 1922, won by Black.} 39... Qc8 $1 {Black threatens ..
.Ne3+ followed by ...Rxd5 and the bad thing is that 40.Kg2 runs into 40...Rxd5!
} 40. e6 {A despaired attack. For a short sequence both sides play perfectly.}
Bd4 $1 41. Rc1 ({If} 41. Nd7 {Black re-opens the d-file and the h3-c8 diagonal
with} Rxd7 $1 42. exd7 Qxd7 43. Rc1 Ne3+ {with a decisive attack for instance}
44. Kxh4 e5 $5 (44... Qxd5 {also wins.}) 45. fxe5 (45. dxe6 Bf6+ {wins the
queen.}) ({Or if} 45. Kg3 Nxd5 {attacking b4 and f4 simultaneously.}) 45...
Qd8+ 46. Kh3 Qg5 {with decisive threats.}) 41... Rxd5 42. Qe4 Ne3 $6 (42... Rd8
$1 $19 {was better as White cannot afford opening the dangerous diagonal with
exf7+.}) 43. f5 $2 ({Missing} 43. Nd7 $1 Qxc1 44. exf7+ Kxf7 45. Qxe7+ Kg8 46.
Qf8+ {with a perpetual.}) 43... Rxf5 $19 44. Re1 Bxc5 45. Bxc5 Qxc5 46. Rxe3 f6
47. f4 Kg7 48. Rd3 Qc1 49. Rf3 Qc4 50. Qe3 g5 51. Qb6 Rxf4 52. Rxf4 Qxf4 53.
Qc6 Qf1+ 0-1

