1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Bd2 {In the past, this used to be
an occasional guest in grandmaster games, but over the past decade it has
turned into one of the main systems. White intends re-capturing on c3 with the
bishop, thus neutralizing the Gruenfeld bishop. This sounds logical, but the
bishops' opposition and probable exchange does not always favour him, as Black
gets chances for a successfull blockade on dark squares. Moreover, the bishop
manoeuvre is a bit time consuming.} Bg7 6. e4 Nxc3 7. Bxc3 O-O {This is an
important crossroads. In principle, Black intends playing ...c7-c5, when the
only principled reaction is d4-d5. He would then play ...e7-e6, opening the
centre and aiming to make use of his slight lead in deevlopment. White has a
wide choice of continuations, some of them allowing Black's plan in optimal
form, but some trying to anticipate it.} 8. Qd2 {This speaks about White's
aggressive intentions. By developing the queen on a dark square he prepares
h2-h4-h5 and also the long castle.} (8. Be2 {delays the knight's development
in order to prevent ...Bg4, but allows the central break under comfortable
circumstances.} c5 9. d5 e6 10. Nf3 exd5 11. exd5 Nd7 {White's passed pawn
will soon turn into a weakness due to White's slight delay in development.} 12.
O-O Nb6 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. d6 Qf6 15. Rc1 Rd8 16. Rxc5 Rxd6 $11 {With complete
equality in Schweda-Groszpeter, Austria 2011.}) (8. Rc1 {anticipates the
advance of the c-pawn by taking over the control of the c-file, but completely
neglects the kingside development.} c5 9. d5 e6 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. Rxc5 {
White has won a pawn but all his kingside pieces are on initial squares,
making it easy for Black to get compensation.} exd5 12. Rxd5 (12. exd5 $2 Qe7+
{wins the rook.}) (12. Qd4+ Kg8 13. exd5 Re8+ 14. Be2 Na6 15. Rc3 Nc7 $17 {
leaves White badly underdeveloped.}) 12... Qe7 13. Be2 ({Or if} 13. Qd4+ Kg8
14. Nf3 Nc6 15. Qe3 Re8 {possibly followed by Black retrieves the pawn with
either ...Qxe4 or ...Be6.}) 13... Qb4+ ({Trying to get more than plane
equality with} 13... Qxe4) 14. Rd2 Nc6 15. Nf3 Bg4 16. a3 Qxe4 17. O-O Rad8 18.
h3 Bxf3 19. Bxf3 Qf4 20. Rxd8 Rxd8 21. Qc1 {1/2-1/2 Rusev-Gupta, Golden Sands
2013.}) ({The natural} 8. Nf3 {is a better way of fighting against ...c7-c5
but it runs into anoher thematic move:} Bg4 $1 ({If} 8... c5 9. d5 e6 {White
has a choice between} 10. Bc4 {and 10.d6, since the knight controls e5,
allowing him consolidating the far advanced pawn.}) 9. Be2 Nc6 10. d5 Bxc3+ 11.
bxc3 Bxf3 12. gxf3 ({As usual, re-capturing with the bishop maintains the
structural flexibility but wastes a tempo:} 12. Bxf3 Ne5 13. Be2 c6 14. c4 cxd5
15. cxd5 Qa5+ 16. Qd2 Qa4 17. f4 Nc4 18. Qd4 Rac8 19. Kf2 Nb6 {with
counterplay on the weakened queenside squares.}) 12... Na5 13. Qd2 e6 ({
This looks more logical than} 13... c6 {as played in Sachdev-Hammer, Reykjavik
2015. The point is that Black can benefit from placing his queenside pawns on
dark squares for the sake of blockading.}) 14. c4 b6 15. h4 ({The over-ambitous
} 15. f4 Qe7 16. e5 {runs into} f6 $17 {when White's centre is vulnerable.})
15... Qf6 {Followed by ...Nb7-c5 with great play on dark squares.}) (8. Bc4 {
Is a more straightforward way of fighting against the plan ...c7-c5 followed
by ...e7-e6 but the bishop will soon be exposed n c4.} Nd7 9. Ne2 c5 10. d5 Ne5
11. Bb3 {In Grischuk-Krasenkow, Saint Vincent 2005 Black would have obtained
strong counterplay after} b5 12. f4 (12. O-O {allows} b4 13. Bxe5 Bxe5 14. Qd2
Ba6 15. Rac1 e6 16. Bc4 Bxc4 17. Rxc4 exd5 18. exd5 Qd6 $15 {With preferable
play since the knight cannot reach c4.}) 12... Ng4 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Qd2 Qb6 {
Black can combine such plans as ...Rd8, ...c5-c4, ...e7-e6 and ...Bb7. His
chances are not worse.}) 8... Nc6 $5 {Even in such a heavily analyzed opening
like the Gruenfeld, Carlsen finds a way of deviating from the main theoretical
discussion. But this is not really such a miracle, since this is a very
flexible opening with practically unlimited possibilities for improvising.} ({
The following game proved} 8... c5 {risky:} 9. d5 Bxc3 10. bxc3 e6 11. d6 e5
12. h4 Be6 13. Nh3 {With a strong attack in Anand-Hammer, Stavanger 2013.}) 9.
Nf3 {The most natural way of defending the central pawn, even though it allows
Black developing freely on the next move.} (9. Ne2 {as tried in
Hambleton-Berson, Portugal Cove 2013 avoids ...Bg4 but places the knight on a
not very active square. Black could obtain good counterplay with} e5 {(not the
only move, most surely)} 10. d5 Nd4 $1 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Bxd4 Re8 (12... Qh4 {
also retrieves the pawn for instance:} 13. Qe3 Re8 14. Bd3 Bf5 $11) 13. f3 Qxd5
14. Bxg7 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Kxg7 $11 {Vallejo-Aronian, Novi Sad 2016.}) ({Without
kingside development, the radical advance} 9. d5 {is not likely to yield too
much:} Ne5 10. Be2 (10. f4 {fails to force the knight onto a unfavourable path:
} Ng4 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 {If anything, the knight could return to f6, followed by ..
.c7-c6.} 12. Nf3 c6 13. dxc6 bxc6 14. h3 Nf6 15. Qc3 Qb6 {Black's activity and
the weaknesses on dark squares in White's camp compensate for the small
structural deffect, Ushenina-Lagno, Beijing 2013.}) 10... c6 11. Nf3 Nxf3+ 12.
Bxf3 Bxc3 13. Qxc3 cxd5 14. exd5 e6 $11 {with complete equality in
Gleizerov-Ulibin, Las Palmas 2014 and Moiseenko-Navara, Germany 2015.}) 9...
Bg4 10. d5 {The only reasonable continuation.} (10. O-O-O $6 {allows the
central break under optimal circumstances:} e5 11. d5 (11. dxe5 Bxf3 12. Qxd8
Raxd8 13. gxf3 Rxd1+ 14. Kxd1 Rd8+ 15. Kc2 Bxe5 $15 {Due to the weaknesses on
dark squares, the knight is stronger than the bishop.}) 11... Nd4 $15 {With a
dream position for Black.}) 10... Bxf3 11. Bxg7 $5 {Strictly speaking, this
looks like a concession since White would be interested in provoking ... Bxc3,
bxc3 with a strengthening of his centre. But Anand had a concrete idea in mind.
} ({If} 11. gxf3 Ne5 12. O-O-O ({Defending the pawn is not necessary.} 12. Be2
{wastes an imprtant tempo and led to comfortable black play in a few games,
the latest being:} c6 13. f4 Nd7 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. dxc6 bxc6 {
Moiseenko-Nepomniachtchi, Yaroslavl 2014.}) 12... c6 ({Even with bishops on
board, the pawn is taboo:} 12... Nxf3 $2 13. Qf4 $18) 13. f4 (13. Qd4 Qd6 14.
f4 $6 {runs into} Bh6 $1 {Lampert-Astaneh Lopez, chess.com 2017.}) 13... Ng4
14. Bxg7 Kxg7 $11 {[%cal Gg4f6] followed by ...Nf6.}) 11... Kxg7 12. gxf3 Ne5
13. O-O-O {The most agressive continuation.} ({As we know, White does not need
defending the f3-pawn yet:} 13. Be2 e6 14. f4 Nd7 15. O-O-O (15. dxe6 fxe6 {
clears the f-file, making the f4-pawn vulnerable.}) 15... Nf6 16. Bf3 exd5 17.
e5 Ne4 18. Bxe4 dxe4 19. Qe3 Qh4 $11 {Bulski-Y. Vovk, Slovakia 2016}) (13. Qc3
f6 14. O-O-O {as played in Karavade-Gupta, Douglas 2016 basically transposes
to the main line after} c6) 13... c6 {This thematic pawn break is not the only
good move.} (13... Nxf3 $2 14. Qc3+) ({Given the move order chosen by Anand 
(compare with what Karavade played above) Black could have avoided the
weakening of his kingside with} 13... Qd6 $5 14. Be2 (14. Qc3 $6 Qf6 15. Be2 c6
$15 {leaves the white centre immobile and vulnerable.}) 14... c6 $11) 14. Qc3
f6 {[%csl Ge6]} 15. Bh3 {This bishops cuts like a blade, but... only on light
squares. The position remains double-edged strategically. Should White allow
some exchanges, he would risk landing into a bad ending, due to his numerous
pawn weaknesses.} ({Pawn grabbing hands in the initiative to Black:} 15. dxc6
$6 Qb6 16. cxb7 $6 Rab8 $15 17. f4 $2 Rxb7 $19 {[%cal Gf8c8,Rb7c7] Threatening
...Rc8 or ...Rc7.}) 15... cxd5 {True to his style, Carlsen clears matters in
the centre with the first given occasion.} 16. exd5 Nf7 {An ultra prophylactic
move anticipating f3-f4.} 17. f4 {Preventing ...Ng5 in order to maintain the
bishop's stability on the good diagonal..} ({The careless} 17. Rhe1 $2 {
runs into} Ng5 {when White has problems due to the potential threat ...Rc8.}) (
{Or if} 17. Kb1 $5 Qd6 {(Preventing f3-f4)} 18. Be6 {Black can free himself
with} Ng5 19. Bg4 Kg8 $1 {Unpinning the f6-pawn.} 20. h4 f5 21. hxg5 fxg4 22.
fxg4 Rxf2 $11) 17... Qb6 $5 {This looks like the start of the optimal
regrouping, fighting against the dominating queen.} ({The intiial game
Anand-Carlsen, Sochi 2014 went} 17... Qd6 {depriving the knight from the
d6-square and allowing White keeping some pressure along the long digonal and
the e-file.}) 18. f3 Nd6 19. Kb1 Nb5 20. Qb4 ({If} 20. Qd3 Rad8 {gains a tempo
due to the threat ...Rxd5 and if Qxd5? then ...Nc3.} 21. Be6 f5 {followed by ..
.Rf6 and ...Nc7 when White's central outposts are in danger.}) 20... Nd6 {
The queen exchange would lead to a comfortable ending for Black and if White
avoids the repetition with} 21. Qd2 f5 $11 {offers Black excellent play. The
bishop is passive and Black already gets the c8-square for his rooks.} *

