1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 ({
The move order based on delaying the knight's development is mainly designed
against Black's plan mentioned in the comments to Black's 9th move does not
affect us:} 7. Be3 c5 8. Qd2 (8. Rc1 Qa5 9. Qd2 O-O {transposes to our main
line or the next comment since White hardly has a better move than} 10. Nf3 {
or 10.d5.}) 8... O-O 9. Rb1 $5 {Since Black has not developed his queen to a5
this is completely inoffensive.} ({But} 9. Rc1 Qa5 {mainly transposes to the
main line since} 10. d5 {exposes White's centre:} e6 11. c4 Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 b6
13. Bd3 f5 {White's king is exposed as proven by several games. An important
point is that} 14. exf5 {should be answered with} gxf5 $1 {keeping the tension
in the centre.}) 9... cxd4 10. cxd4 Nc6 {Black starts the fight against the
central pawn without spending a tempo on moving with his queen.} 11. d5 (11.
Nf3 {allows Black bringing one more piece into play, with the same purpose:
undermining d4.} Bg4 12. d5 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Ne5 14. Be2 Qc8 $1 {A fine move
solving Black's problems. The immediate threats are ...Nxf3+ and if Bxf3 then .
..Bc3, or simply ...Nc4 and ...Qh3.} 15. O-O Qh3 16. Qd1 {Black has several
good moves, for instance 16...f5, but if he wishes he already can force a draw
with} Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 Be5 18. Re1 Bxh2+) 11... Ne5 12. Be2 b6 {Since White will
need some time to expel the central knight Black can switch to the slow mode.
The last move prepares ...Bb7 but also takes the pawn out of the rook's range,
freeing the c8-bishop.} 13. h3 ({Or if} 13. f4 Ng4 14. Bd4 e5 15. fxe5 Nxe5 16.
Nf3 Qd6 $5 {with a pleasant blockade.}) 13... Bb7 {Planning ...e7-e6 or ...
f7-f5.} 14. f4 Nd7 15. Nf3 Rc8 16. Bd4 (16. O-O Nc5 17. Qb4 {is somewhat
better but Black has good counterplay after} f5 {anyway.}) 16... Bxd4 17. Qxd4
Qc7 {Suddenly White experiences problems on dark squares.} 18. Qd2 Nf6 19. Bd3
Nh5 $17 {Gilman-Prahov,Montreal 2000.}) 7... c5 8. Be3 {This system became
popular in the late '70s, causing Black lots of problems proving the viabiity
of the gruenfeld defence in general, and it has not lost its actuality up to
today. White intends keeping the integrity of his centre hoping that this will
offer him a stable advantage in the middlegame. Earlier, all these systems
with Nf3 were considered inoffensive because of the possible ...Bg4, which was
due to a static evaluation of the position. Decades ago, the young Kasparov
was the main hero of this system, but then Karpov took it up into his
repertoire to play it in his matches with Kasparov himself. Over the past
decades another great K, Vladimir Kramnik, became the main specialist with
white.} Qa5 9. Qd2 {This is the main line but White has two important
alternatives in} (9. Nd2 {and}) (9. Bd2 {which will be examined in Lines 2 and
3.}) 9... O-O ({Traditionally,} 9... Nc6 {is considered the most effective
system, but White can side-step it using the move order indicated above.
Moreover, I believe that} 10. Rb1 {causes some problems. In a similar position
from Line 3 I recommend} b6 {but with the knight on c6 this allows White
gaining a tempo for his development with} 11. Bb5 $14) 10. Rc1 ({For} 10. Rb1 {
see Line 3.}) 10... Bg4 {Black has tried a wide range of moves in this
position, but the one I examine is very typical for the whole opening by
increasing the pressure on d4.} 11. d5 {The critical answer, as White does not
have simple ways of living with the pressure on d4.} ({The developing} 11. Be2
{is slow, allowing Black a tempo for building up his counterplay.} e6 {Black
anticipates d4-d5, reckoning with the fact that due to the pins along the
e1-a5 and d1-h5 diagonals White has no challenging alternative.} (11... Nd7 {
is also possible, with a possible transposition to Itkis-Tseshkovsky below.}
12. d5) 12. d5 (12. Bh6 {basically loses a pawn without offering adequate
attacking chances:} Bxh6 13. Qxh6 Bxf3 14. gxf3 cxd4 15. h4 {In J.
Fernandez-Banas, Trnava 1980 Black played 15...dxc3 when 16.h5 offered White
easonable compensation.} Rc8 $1 {was stronger for instance} 16. h5 Rxc3 17. Rd1
Rc5+ 18. Kf1 Rxh5 $17) ({Or if} 12. O-O Bxf3 13. Bxf3 cxd4 14. cxd4 Qxd2 15.
Bxd2 Bxd4 16. Rc7 Na6 17. Rxb7 Bb6 {[%cal Ga6c5] followed by ... Nc5 Black has
excellent play on dark squares.}) 12... exd5 13. exd5 Nd7 14. c4 ({Aiming to
consolidate White's space advantage for if} 14. O-O Nb6 {the knight would
start exerting pressure on the whole queenside.}) 14... Qxd2+ 15. Nxd2 ({
This allows Black freeing his play by exchanging the bishop, but} 15. Kxd2 {
exposes the king:} Nf6 16. Bd3 {In Melkumyan-Malisauskas, Warsaw 2009 the most
energetic way of obtaining counterplay was} b5 {causing White some trouble
along the d-file. A possible continuation is} 17. Ne5 Rfd8 18. Nxg4 Nxg4 19.
Bxc5 Ne5 $11 {With general exchanges and a most likely draw.}) 15... Bxe2 16.
Kxe2 f5 $11 {With comfortable equality in Nadimifar-Darini, Mashhad 2014.}) (
11. Ne5 {gains te bishops pair but delays the development:} cxd4 12. cxd4 Qxd2+
13. Bxd2 Bxe5 14. dxe5 Nc6 15. Bc3 Be6 16. a3 Rac8 17. Bb2 Na5 $15 {Martorell
Aguado-Valls Marti, Barcelona 2013. Black's initiative prevents White from
enjoying the latent force of his bishops.}) (11. Ng5 {is the most consistent
alternative to the main move.} cxd4 (11... h6 $6 {achieves only the queenside
weakening after} 12. h3 $1 $14) 12. cxd4 Nc6 13. Qxa5 {A logical reply,
releasing the pressure on d4.} ({The untested} 13. d5 {offers Black
counterplay in many ways, for instance} Nb4 $5 14. Rc4 (14. Bc4 {exposes the
bishop to} b5) 14... Rfc8 $1 {A sacrifice justified by White's delay in
development.} 15. Qxb4 Qxb4+ 16. Rxb4 Bc3+ 17. Bd2 Bxb4 18. Bxb4 Rc2 19. f3 Bd7
20. Bxe7 Rac8 {The rooks activity is threatening already so the knight should
hurry back to the defence.} 21. Nh3 Rxa2 22. Nf2 Rc1+ 23. Nd1 Ba4 24. Be2 Rcc2
25. Bf1 b5 $15 {followed by ...a7-a5 and ...b5-b4. With most of his pieces on
the back rank White has serious problems reacting to this plan.}) ({Or if} 13.
h3 Qxd2+ 14. Kxd2 {as in Ozolin-Bezzubenkov, Izhevsk 2011} Bc8 15. d5 Rd8 16.
Ke1 (16. Kc2 Nd4+ 17. Kd3 Nb5 {the knight regroups flexibly.}) 16... Nd4 $13 {
Black plans ...e7-e6 with adequate counterplay. If} 17. Rc4 $6 Nb5 $1 18. Rxc8
Raxc8 19. Bxb5 Rc2 20. Bd2 Rxa2 21. Ke2 e6 22. Bc4 Rb2 23. Rc1 b5 {Black's
rooks and queenside pawns once again cause White problems.}) 13... Nxa5 14. h3
(14. Be2 {offers Black prospects of invading the c4-square.} Bxe2 15. Kxe2 Rfc8
16. Nf3 Nc4 17. Nd2 Nxd2 18. Kxd2 Rd8 19. Rc4 {In Yermolinsky-Svidler, Elista
1998 the simplest way of forcing a draw was} b5 20. Rb4 a5 21. Rxb5 Bxd4 22.
Rhb1 Bxe3+ 23. Kxe3 Rac8 24. Rxa5 Rc3+ 25. Kf4 Rd2 26. Rf1 Rcc2 27. Kf3 $11)
14... Bd7 15. Bd3 ({With incomplete development the rook's activation is
premature:} 15. Rc7 Rfd8 16. Bd2 b6 {followed by ...Rac8.}) 15... Rfc8 16. Kd2
b5 {Preparing the knight jump to c4.} 17. Nf3 a6 ({In principle the structure
arising after} 17... Nc4+ 18. Bxc4 bxc4 $11 {offers White the possibility of
blocking on c3, but Black has enough dynamic resources to retain good play:}
19. Kc3 $5 Rc5 $5 {followed by ...Ra5.}) 18. g4 h6 {Drawn in San
Segundo-Svidler, San Sebastian 2009.}) 11... Nd7 ({It is useful delaying the
exchange on f3. The old line, based on three games by Romanischin goes} 11...
Bxf3 12. gxf3 Nd7 13. c4 Qc7 ({Or if} 13... Qa3 {aiming at transposing to our
main line White could consider} 14. h4) 14. f4 {White grabs his chance by
putting his massive centre into motion at once. In our main line he cannot do
that, of course.} e5 15. fxe5 Nxe5 16. Be2 Qe7 17. f4 Nd7 18. Bf3 $16 {
Khenkin-Romanishin, Ohrid 2001.}) (11... Na6 {looks flexible but deevlops the
knight too far from the kingside and from the centre.} 12. h4 f5 13. exf5 Bxf5
14. h5 $16 {Kramnik-Svidler, Moscow 2009.}) 12. c4 {White should consolidate
his centre at once.} ({The developing} 12. Be2 {allows} c4 13. Bd4 (13. O-O Nc5
14. Qc2 Rac8 {offers Black excellent queenside play.}) (13. Bxc4 $2 Rac8 $17 {
causes big problems with the c3-pawn.}) 13... Bxf3 14. gxf3 (14. Bxf3 {weakens
the control over d3 allowing} Nc5 15. Bxg7 Nd3+ $11) 14... Rac8 15. Bxg7 Kxg7
16. h4 f6 17. f4 Nc5 {with complex play and roughly equal chances in
Itkis-Tseshkovsky, Krasnodar 1980.}) ({The untested} 12. h4 {is less effective
than with the black knight on a6.} Nf6 13. c4 (13. e5 Nd7 {leaves the white
centre vulnerable without offering him realistic attacking chances.} 14. Nh2 h5
15. Nxg4 hxg4 16. h5 Nxe5 17. Bh6 Qb6 $11 {Black prepares ...Qxg6, securing
his king.}) 13... Qc7 14. Bd3 (14. e5 Ne4 15. Qc2 Qa5+ 16. Nd2 Nxd2 17. Bxd2
Qc7 18. f4 e6 {followed by ...f7-f6 soon is also pleasant for Black.}) 14...
Bxf3 15. gxf3 Nh5 16. f4 e5 {with a pleasant blockade on dark squares.}) 12...
Qa3 {The queen stands well on this square, putting pressure on the queenside
but also keeping an eye on the opposite wing. Any retreat along the initial
diagonal would count as a loss of time.} 13. Be2 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 (14. gxf3 {
is answered in the same way:} Bd4 $1 {fighting for the control over the dark
squares even at the cost of one pawn.} 15. O-O (15. f4 e5 16. O-O exf4 17. Bxf4
Rfe8 $11) 15... e5 16. dxe6 (16. Bh6 Rfb8 $5 {Defending the b7-pawn in
anticipation of Rb1, preparing ...b7-b5 and planning ...Nf6.} 17. f4 Qh3 18.
fxe5 Nxe5 19. Bf4 b5 20. cxb5 Rxb5 $36) 16... fxe6 17. Bxd4 cxd4 18. Qxd4 {
In Sibashvili-Gledura, Gyor 2014 the most effective way of developing the
counterplay on dark squares was} Nc5 19. Rcd1 Qa5 20. Qe5 Rf7 $11) 14... Bd4 $1
{Here, too, this is the best way of fighting for the dark squares, turning the
knight at least as strong as the f3-bishop.} 15. Bxd4 ({It makes no sense
leaving Black with a strong bishop in the centre.} 15. Bh6 Rfe8 16. h4 e6 $132)
15... cxd4 16. O-O Ne5 17. Qxd4 {This leads to an interesting position with
major pieces.} ({Keeping the bishop offers Black stron counterplay anyway:} 17.
Be2 d3 18. Rc3 ({Or if} 18. Bd1 Rac8 19. Bb3 Qc5 {Prventing f2-f4 and planning
the next move.} 20. Kh1 Qd4 {dooming the c4-pawn}) (18. Qe3 Rac8 19. c5 Qa5 20.
Bd1 Rfd8 $5 {Anticipating Bg4 after the inevitable ...Nd7.} 21. f4 Nd7 22. Bg4
Rxc5 $11) 18... dxe2 $1 19. Rxa3 exf1=Q+ 20. Kxf1 Nxc4 21. Qb4 Nxa3 22. Qxa3
Rfe8 $11 {White's space advantage compensates for the slight material
disadvantage, but the force of the rooks should not be underestimated.}) ({
Or if} 17. Bd1 Rac8) 17... Nxf3+ 18. gxf3 Qxf3 19. Rc3 Qe2 {In this
interesting position the black queen's activity reveals the double-edged
character of White's optically impressive space advantage. The far advanced
pawns have weakened the back ranks and also the king.} 20. f4 {White
sacrifices the a2-pawn in order to speed up his attack.} (20. a4 {offers Black
an additional tempo to organize his counterplay against c4:} b6 21. f4 Rac8 22.
a5 Rc5 23. axb6 axb6 24. f5 Rfc8 $11) 20... Qxa2 21. f5 b6 22. e5 Qb2 {The
position remains complcated with chances for both sides, but Black's win in
Kramnik-Grischuk, Stavanger 2014 suggests that his position is somewhat easier
to handle.} *

