1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8.
Be3 Qa5 9. Qd2 O-O 10. Rb1 {This manoeuvre, aimed at harassig the enemy queen
and thus provoking a small concession such as ...a7-a6 before the rook goes to
c1 to defend c3, is typical in the line with 9...Nc6 mentioned in Line 1, but
here it is harmless.} b6 {The simplest way of neutralizing the rook's pressure
along the b-file, at the same time preparing the bishop's development to
either b7 or a6.} 11. Rc1 {The most popular move and a typical one in the 9...
Nc6 lines. But in this case ...b7-b6 is not a concession.} (11. Rb5 {fails
troubling the black queen.} Qa4 12. Rb3 ({With incomplete development White
should refrain from pawn grabbing:} 12. dxc5 Nc6 {Preparing ...Ba6 without
allowing Rb4.} 13. cxb6 {In Trifonov-Kharitonov, Kirov 2015 Black's most
active continuation would have been} Ba6 14. Rb3 Bxf1 15. Kxf1 axb6 $17 {
White has an extra pawn and a target on b6, but Black has a big advance in
development and three targets on a2, c3 and e4.}) 12... Ba6 {The bishops
exchange weakens the light squares in White's camp and causes him some
problems with castling.} 13. Bxa6 Qxa6 14. Qe2 ({Pawn grabbing with an
insecured king is once again risky:} 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. Bxc5 Rc8 16. Bd4 Bxd4
17. cxd4 Nd7 $17 {followed by ...Nb6 and White still has problems finding a
way to evacuate the king.}) 14... Rc8 ({I slightly prefer this over} 14...
Qxe2+ 15. Kxe2 {as in Thirion-Viviani, Porto Mannu Palau 2016 since this helps
White's development.}) 15. Qxa6 Nxa6 16. Kd2 e6) ({The solid} 11. Bd3 {
defending e4 has the drawback of weakening the defence on d4 and is logically
met by} Nc6 12. Rb5 (12. e5 {weakens the d5-square chronically without
offering White realistic kingside attacking chances.} Rd8 13. Rb5 Qa4 14. Rb2
Ba6 15. Bxa6 Qxa6 16. Qe2 Qa4 17. O-O cxd4 18. cxd4 Rac8 19. h4 {In Rivas
Pastor-Epishin, Dos Hermanas 1994 19...h5 20.e6 f5 led to complications, but}
Nb4 {followed by either ...Nd5 or ...Nc2 offers Black pleasant play at no cost.
}) 12... Qa4 13. Rb2 Ba6 14. O-O Bxd3 15. Qxd3 cxd4 16. cxd4 Rfd8 {White
already has problems along the d-file.} 17. Qd1 {In Ben Menachem-Liss, Ramat
Hasharon 1992 Black went 17...Qa3 with a pleasant position but he could have
also used the pin along the d-file with} Qxd1 18. Rxd1 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 (19. Rxd4
Bxd4 20. Bxd4 Rac8 21. h3 Rc4 22. Be3 Rxe4 {offers Black the better ending.})
19... e5 {with a probable draw. If anything, only White may struggle slightly.}
) 11... Bb7 {Curiously, this logical move has been seen only once.} 12. d5 {
The most principled move, but since White practically threw a tempo away it is
not likely that he can maintain his centre intact for long.} (12. Bd3 {does
not prevent White from committing after} Rd8 {The pressure against d4 is
becoming unpleasant already.} 13. d5 ({White has no time for attacking o the
kingside:} 13. h4 cxd4 14. cxd4 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Nc6 16. d5 Nb4 {Threatening ...
e7-e6 or ...f7-f5.} 17. Rc7 {The simplest way of achieving a pleasant position
is} Bxd5 18. exd5 Rxd5 19. Ne1 Rad8 $15 {retrieving the piece with light
initiative.}) 13... c4 {Preventing White from consolidating with c3-c4.} 14.
Bxc4 {Otherwise Black would break with ...e7-e6.} Rc8 15. Qd3 Ba6 16. Bxa6
Bxc3+ 17. Ke2 Nxa6 {with excellent queenside play.}) 12... Nd7 {Preparing the
thematic ...c5-c4.} 13. Bd3 ({As in so many cases White's centre is not that
stable after} 13. c4 Qxd2+ 14. Nxd2 e6 15. Be2 Rae8 {followed by ...f7-f5.}) ({
Black can also stop the attack initiated by} 13. h4 {with} Nf6 14. Qc2 c4 15.
Bxc4 Rac8 16. Nd2 Ng4 17. Bg5 b5 18. Be2 Rxc3 {with enough counterplay.}) 13...
c4 $1 {Everything is prepared now for this.} 14. Bb1 (14. Bxc4 {is even worse
than in the previous line since ...Nd7 is more useful than ...Rd8.} Rac8 15.
Qd3 Rxc4 16. Qxc4 Rc8 17. Qb3 Ba6 $17 {with a strong attack against the
uncastled king.}) 14... e6 ({This is more straightforward than} 14... Nc5 {
which is also viable, but offers White some attacking chances:} 15. Bh6 e6 16.
Bxg7 Kxg7 $13 {Portisch-Sarno, Reggio Emilia 1992. After the suggested move
White has no time for Bh6 anymore.}) 15. dxe6 Nc5 16. exf7+ Rxf7 17. O-O (17.
Bxc5 Qxc5 18. O-O b5 {followed by ...a7-a5, ...b5-b4 and possibly by doubling
rooks on the e-file turns the g7-bishop very strong while White's extra pawn
does not mean much.}) 17... Bxe4 18. Ng5 Rd7 19. Qe2 Bd3 20. Qf3 Rad8 21. Bxc5
Qxc5 (21... bxc5 {is also good enough.}) 22. Bxd3 cxd3 23. Ne6 Qc4 24. Nxd8 d2
25. Rcd1 Rxd8 {Black will play ...Bxc3 soon with entirely adequate
compensation for the exchange.} *

