1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8.
Be3 Qa5 9. Nd2 {An interesting move which enjoys some popularity lately. The
knight approaches the queenside aiming at harassing the enemy queen.} Bd7 $5 {
Black slightly deviates from the classical developing move order (first the
knights and only then the bishops). The last move has a series of concrete
ideas. Apart from the obvious threat ... Ba4, which, in some cases, gets the
c2-square for the queen after forced operations in the centre, he also
prepares ...Qa4, taking the queen out of the knight's range without returning
on the initial diagonal.} ({White's idea is revealed after} 9... cxd4 10. Nc4
Qd8 (10... Qxc3+ $2 11. Bd2 {traps the queen.}) 11. cxd4 O-O 12. Rc1 {White
has transferred the knight on an active position without losing time since the
queen has returned to its initial square. In doing so he avoided the usual
problems along the e1-a5 diagonal.} f5 {the only attempt at obtaining
counterplay.} 13. Qb3 Kh8 14. Ne5 $14) ({And if} 9... Qxc3 10. Rc1 Qa3 11. Rxc5
{retrieves the pawn with initiative.}) 10. Rb1 {The most frequent move, trying
to highlight the weakening of the b7-pawn and taking measures against ...Ba4 
(see below)..} ({the developing} 10. Be2 {allows} Ba4 $146 11. Qc1 ({Or if} 11.
Qb1 cxd4 12. Nc4 Qxc3+ 13. Bd2 {Black has} Qc2 $1) 11... cxd4 12. Bxd4 {
Sad necessity.} (12. Nc4 {is ineffective because} Qxc3+ {exchanges queens.}) (
12. cxd4 Nc6 13. d5 Nd4 $17 {offers Black overwhelming initiative in which the
a4-bishop plays an important part.}) 12... O-O {With perfect play for Black
due to his better structure.}) (10. Nb3 {is just a way to force a draw by
repetition:} Qxc3+ 11. Bd2 Qb2 12. Bc1 Qc3+ 13. Bd2 Qb2 14. Bc1 Qc3+ 15. Bd2 {
Drawn Ju,W-Sutovsky, Caleta 2017.}) ({Unlike the main move,} 10. Rc1 {defends
c3 but frees Black of worries along the b-file.} cxd4 11. cxd4 (11. Nc4 {
is met with} Qa4 12. Qxa4 Bxa4 13. cxd4 O-O 14. Be2 Rd8 15. d5 Na6 16. Na5 Nb4
{with good counterplay, once again based on the bishop's activity.}) 11... O-O
12. Bc4 Ba4 13. Bb3 Bb5 14. a4 Ba6 15. Bc4 {In Deac-Areshchenko, Calimanesti
2016 Black should have refrained from the exchange on c4 as the mutual bishop
tension slightly favours him:} Nc6 16. O-O Rac8 ({Preparing ...Nxd4, which
would lose a piece if played at once:} 16... Nxd4 $2 17. Bxd4 Bxd4 18. Nb3 $18)
17. d5 (17. Bxa6 Qxa6 18. Nf3 e6 {offers Black perfect coordination.}) ({
In order to illustrate Black's tactical threat I chose the neutral} 17. h3 $2
Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Bxd4 19. Nb3 Qb4 20. Bxa6 Rxc1 $1 {This is the point. White is
forced reducing the attack against the bishop.} 21. Qxc1 bxa6 $17) 17... Ne5
18. Bxa6 Qxa6 {With active counterplay on White's weakened queenside.}) 10...
Qxc3 {Now that the rook has already spent a tempo on developing this is
entirely playable.} ({One important idea behind White's last move is that} 
10... Ba4 {allows} 11. Qxa4+ $1 Qxa4 12. Bb5+ Qxb5 13. Rxb5 $14 {with some
light pressure Melkumyan-Khalifman, Moscow 2012.}) 11. d5 ({Or if} 11. dxc5 Bc6
12. Bb5 {as in Fressinet-Grandelius, Germany 2013 Black equalizes easily with}
O-O 13. O-O Bd4 $11) (11. Rc1 Qa3 12. Rxc5 {is not dangerous since Black has
an extra tempo with respect to a line above.} Na6 $5 {with comfortable
development.}) 11... b6 12. Bc4 {Black needs wasting some time to complete his
development which offers White adequate compensation for the pawn but as
practice shows not more.} (12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O {as played in
Prizant-Kowsarinia, St Petersburg 2014 allows undermining the centre with} e6)
12... O-O 13. O-O Qa5 {Preparing ...Ba4 and ...Nd7.} 14. Bb3 Qa6 15. Re1 (15.
a4 {restricts the bishop but provides the knight with an excellent square:} Qb7
16. Nc4 Na6 {followed by ...Nb4.}) 15... Bb5 16. Bg5 c4 {Finally putting the
majority into motion. As a result Black will return the extra pawn but
complete his development.} 17. a4 cxb3 18. axb5 Qxb5 19. Bxe7 Re8 20. Rxb3 Qa4
21. Bd6 Nd7 {An interesting position with highly non-symmetrical structure.
Black is quite active already which causes White problems keeping his centre
intact.} 22. Qb1 ({Consolidating e4 with} 22. f3 {allows} Qd4+ 23. Kh1 a5 {
when the black pawns become dngerous.}) 22... Rac8 23. Ra3 Qc2 24. Qxc2 Rxc2
25. Rxa7 Rxd2 26. Rxd7 Rxd5 $1 $11 {Parligras-Ipatov, Baku 2016.} *

