1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8.
Be3 Qa5 {The other alternative to the main move (9.Qd2) is} 9. Bd2 {,
inhibiting the exchange on d4. But even though this creates Black some
concrete problems, But if Black reacts correctly the move is just as it seems
at the first sight, a waste of time.} O-O 10. Be2 {This is the main move when
Black should play the thematic} (10. h3 {This rare move prevents Black from
increasing the pressure on d4 with ...Bg4 but wastes just another tempo. I
suggest the new move:} Qa3 $5 {moving with the queen out of the bishop's range
when the threats against the white centre will soon become real. Here are a
few possible continuations:} 11. Rb1 (11. Qb3 Qxb3 12. axb3 {only apparently
strengthens White's centre. In fact, it only weakens the b4-square after} cxd4
13. cxd4 Nc6 14. Be3 Rd8 15. Rd1 e6 {Slowing down the white centre.} 16. Be2 b6
17. O-O Bb7 {[%cal Gc6a5] Black already threatens ...Na5 with a double attack,
pracctically frocing White to advance one of his central pawns and thus allow
the activation of Black's pieces. In this line one important problem for White
is that he was not in time to play the king's rook to d1, leaving the other
one available for queenside jobs.}) (11. Bc4 {exposes the bishop to the enemy
knight after} Nc6 12. d5 Na5 13. Be2 e6 {Safer thyan the immediate pawn
grabbing.} 14. O-O exd5 15. exd5 {and now Black could already consider} Bxc3) (
11. Be2 {is more solid but allows} b6 12. O-O cxd4 13. cxd4 Bb7 $11 {and again
White has problems maintaining the integrity of his centre.}) 11... b6 12. Bc4
({If} 12. Rb3 {Black can safely take the pawn as the rook does not stay too
well on b3.} Qxa2 13. Bc4 Be6 14. d5 Bd7 $15) ({Or if} 12. Qc2 Bd7 {planning ..
.Ba4} 13. Bc4 cxd4 14. cxd4 Nc6 15. d5 Ne5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 {In one of my
articles about structures I have mentioned that this structure without knights
tends favouring White, but here he is not optimally cordinated allowing Black
to equalize comfortably.} 17. O-O Rfc8 18. Qd3 Qxd3 19. Bxd3 e6 {Neutralizing
the centre with comfortable play.}) 12... e6 13. O-O Ba6 14. Bxa6 Qxa6 $11 {
Black has pleasant control over the light squares and with his bishop in the
queen's way White is not ready for advancing his d-pawn.}) ({The untested} 10.
c4 Qa3 11. d5 Bxa1 12. Qxa1 {does not offer White enough compensation due to
his incomplete development. The most active continuation is} Na6 13. Bh6 f6 {
followed by ... Nb4.}) 10... Bg4 11. O-O ({If} 11. Qb3 cxd4 12. cxd4 Qb6 13.
Qxb6 axb6 $17 {the queen exchange once again favours Black, who has developed
his queen's rook without moving it. Volodin-Nyback, Finland 2012.}) ({And once
again the exchange sacrifice does not work:} 11. c4 Qa3 12. d5 Bxa1 13. Qxa1 f6
14. Bh6 {Since White is ready for castling, it is better to refrain already
from ...Na6 and play the natural} Nd7 15. Bxf8 Bxf3 16. gxf3 {Clearing the
king's path to g2 in case of ...Qb4+.} Rxf8 17. O-O Ne5 18. Kg2 g5 $15 {
With great play on dark squares.}) 11... Rd8 12. Rb1 (12. Ng5 {frees Black's
play.} Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Qa6 14. Qxa6 Nxa6 15. d5 c4 $15 {In the absence of queens
White has no kingside attacking chances making his queenside weaknesses more
relevant, Kortschnoj-Smirin, Biel 2002.}) 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Qxa2 {Black has
obtained a version of the 8.Rb1 line with an extra tempo due to White's
Bc1-e3-d2.} 14. d5 ({Of course White could think of more or less forcing a
draw by repetition with} 14. Ra1 Qb2 15. Rb1 Qa2 16. Ra1 Qb2 17. Rb1 Qa2 {
½-½ Gelashvili-Mchedlishvili, Lagodekhi 2016.}) 14... Nd7 15. Rxb7 ({White
is best adviced taking the pawn while still possible. If} 15. Bg5 Nc5 16. Rb4
Bf6 $15 {he has no adequate compensation, Volodin-Kolosowski, Finland 2013.})
15... Nc5 16. Rb4 (16. Rxe7 Bf6 17. Rc7 Nxe4 {leaves the d5-pawn vulnerable.
Here is one of the moments when the extra move ...Rd8 is important.}) 16... a5
17. Rc4 Nb3 {Black has used the time spent by White for retrieving the pawn to
get serious queenside counterplay.} 18. Bg5 Bxf3 19. Bxf3 Bf6 20. Rc2 Qa3 21.
Be3 a4 {With active play, compensating for White's bishops pair and compact
centre Roiz-Avrukh, Netanya 2009.} *

