1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8.
Rb1 O-O 9. Be2 {I believe it is safe to say that this is the most analyzed
system in the Gruenfeld. It first became populr almost at the same time with 8.
Be3. White's main idea is clearing the long diagonal in order to speed up the
thematic d4-d5, eve though in many cases this implies a pawn sacrifice. In
practice Black has tried out many plans, and a huge amount of theory has
accumulated in all of them.} Nc6 {As always in unclear situations I prefer the
developing move. Even though the last move does not manage calming down
White's attacking impetu completely, I find it safer and easier to handle than
the pawn grabbing plans.} 10. d5 Ne5 (10... Bxc3+ 11. Bd2 Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Na5
13. h4 {offers White excellent attacking chances, while Black has to struggle
for re-activating the knight.}) 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 {This type of positions with
four bishops and without knights have a marked drawish character if things
stay calm. But White has many dynamic ideas, requiring accuracy from Black. On
the other hand, in playing actively he also needs taking some responsibility
as in the resulting fight Black's structure frequently is more compact.} 12.
Qd2 {This is the most natural way of defending the pawn and by far the main
line. The queen keeps all the important areas under control but the drawback
of the last move is that the c1-bishop remains passive for a while.} (12. Qc2 {
places the queen on the vulnerable b1-h7 diagonal.} e6 13. f4 Bg7 14. dxe6 ({
One important point is that after} 14. c4 exd5 15. cxd5 Re8 {16.e5 is
impossible due to the hanging d5-pawn and} 16. O-O {allows} Rxe4 17. Qxe4 Bf5
$17) 14... Bxe6 15. Rxb7 Qa5 16. Bd2 Qxa2 $11 {Ubilava-Pribyl, Sochi 1984.}) ({
If} 12. c4 {Black can take the pawn without risking too much:} Qa5+ 13. Bd2
Qxa2 14. O-O Bd4 15. Bh6 Re8 16. Bd3 Qa6 {followed by ...Qd6 or ...Qf6 and ...
e7-e6/e5.}) ({If} 12. Rb3 {the most straightforward answer is} c4 13. Bxc4 Qc7
14. Qe2 Bg4 15. Qxg4 ({Or if} 15. f3 {as in Ortega Hermida-Alvarado Diaz, Las
Palmas 2013 play would take a similar course as in the main line after} Rac8
16. fxg4 Qxc4 {when the c3- and e4-pawns are hanging, compensating for White's
material advantage.}) 15... Qxc4 16. Bd2 b6 17. Qe2 Rfc8 18. f4 Bg7 19. Kf2 Qa4
20. Rhb1 Qxa2 21. e5 f6 {1/2-1/2 (30) Shulman,Y (2632)-Kamsky,G (2720) Saint
Louis 2009}) 12... e6 {Black needs breaking the impressive centre before White
gets coordinated with c3-c4 and Bb2.} 13. f4 (13. c4 {is premature due to} Qh4
{when White has problems keeping his centre together for instance} 14. Bf3 Re8)
13... Bc7 $5 {It is strategically desirable to force White re-capturing on d5
with the e-pawn, which would reduce the dynamism of his centre and make f2-f4
looking like a weakness. The point behind the last move is precisely
preventing c3-c4 (and cxd5, of course). Practice has shown that White cannot
use the long diagonal for an attack easily.} ({The old main line goes} 13...
Bg7 14. c4 Re8 15. e5 f6 16. d6 fxe5 17. Bb2 exf4 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. O-O {
with tremenduous compensation for White.}) 14. Bc4 {White intends
strengthening his control in the centre but this supposes wasting a tempo in a
moment when his king is still in the centre.} (14. dxe6 {is inoffensive:} Qxd2+
15. Bxd2 Bxe6 16. Rxb7 Bb6 17. a4 Rfe8 {[%cal Ge6c8] Threatening to trap the
rook with ...Bc8.} 18. Bb5 Bc8 19. Bxe8 Bxb7 20. Bb5 {In Browne -Ftacnik, San
Francisco 1999 Black's most active continuation would have been} c4 {
Threatening ...Bxe4, which would put White's kingside in danger.} 21. Ke2 {
Necessary in order to neutralize one of the threatening bishops.} Bxe4 22. Be3
Rd8 $11) ({The most popular continuation} 14. O-O {is covered in line 7.})
14... a6 {Immediately taking measures against the active bishop.} 15. a4 ({
Once again releasing the tension does not promis much even though for
different reasons.} 15. dxe6 Qxd2+ 16. Bxd2 fxe6 {Due to the hanging f4-pawn
White has no time to prevent ...b7-b5, offering Black active counterplay,
Neuman-Ftacnik, Czechia 2004.}) 15... b5 {The most direct way of annihilating
White's space advantage.} 16. axb5 axb5 17. Bxb5 (17. Rxb5 $2 Ba6 18. Rxc5 Bb6
19. Rc6 Bb7 {traps the rook.}) 17... exd5 18. Bc6 (18. exd5 $6 {exposes the
white king.} Bf5 19. Rb2 c4 {Threatening to keep the king in the centre with ..
.Bb6} 20. O-O Bd3 $17 {Black wins an exchange since} 21. Re1 $2 Qxd5 {followed
by ...Rfb8 traps the bishop.}) ({Or if} 18. Qxd5 $5 Qxd5 19. exd5 Bf5 20. Rb2 {
Black has several ways of using his bishops' activity and advance in
development.} Ba5 ({Nevem gives} 20... Bxf4 21. Bxf4 Ra1+ 22. Kf2 Rxh1 23. Rd2
{when White's compensation may suffice just for equality, but the d-pawn
sustained by the bishops looks annoying.}) 21. Rb3 Rfb8 {Pinning the bishop
and threatening ...Be4 without allowing the intermediate Bc6.} 22. Kf2 Bc2 23.
Rb2 Bxc3 24. Rxc2 Bd4+ 25. Be3 Rxb5 $11 {with an obvious draw.}) 18... Ra6 19.
Bxd5 {Trying to maintain the integrity of the centre.} (19. Qxd5 $2 Qe7 $19 {
leaves White helplessly hanging due to the threats ...Rd8 and ...Be6.}) (19.
exd5 {allows Black activating his light-squared bishop:} Bf5 20. Rb7 ({The
only move. By attacking the bishop White does not give his opponent full
freedom for his attack. If} 20. Rb2 $2 Rxc6 21. dxc6 Re8+ 22. Kf2 Qh4+ 23. g3
Qh3 {White is in trouble.}) 20... Rxc6 $5 {Just one of the good continuations.}
21. dxc6 Qe8+ 22. Qe3 Qxc6 {Due to the hanging g2 pawn White needs returning
the exchange with} 23. Rxc7 Qxc7 $11) 19... Rd6 20. O-O Bf5 $1 {A strong move
shaking the apparently strong white centre.} 21. Qc2 Rxd5 22. exf5 Rxf5 $11 {
Smirin-Neven, Calgary 1996.} *

