1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8.
Rb1 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. d5 Ne5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Qd2 e6 13. f4 Bc7 14. O-O {
Given the problems caused in the previous line by the king's delay in the
centre this move is quite natural.} exd5 15. exd5 Ba5 {This is an important
move in Black's strategy. Since the queen does not have good squares the pin
along the e1-a5 diagonal prevents the dangerous c3-c4 followed by Bb2.} 16. d6
{The best way of keeping the game complicated. White simply advances his pawn,
preventing the blocking ...Qd6 and without committing himself in any other way.
} ({The aggressive} 16. f5 {leads to mass simplifications and a probable draw:}
Bxf5 17. Rxb7 Qd6 18. Bc4 Rfb8 19. Rxb8+ (19. Qb2 $5 Rxb7 20. Qxb7 Re8 21. Bf4
Qb6 $13 {is also safe for Black (Krasenkow)}) ({Or if} 19. Rb3 Rxb3 20. axb3 {
White improves his structure only symbolically since the weakness of the
c3-pawn persists.} Re8 21. Re1 Re5 22. Re3 Bc7 23. g3 h5 24. Rxe5 Qxe5 25. Qe3
{1/2-1/2 Zacks -Etaoin Shrdlu playchess.com 2007.}) 19... Rxb8 20. Qg5 Rb1 {
Neutralizing any attacking attempts.} 21. Bf4 ({Krasenkow also gives} 21. Re1
Qd8 $5 22. Qe3 Bc7 $11 {[%cal Yc7d6] followed by ...Bd6.}) 21... Rxf1+ 22. Kxf1
Qb6 {Heading for a draw by perpetual.} 23. Be5 Qb1+ 24. Kf2 Qc2+ 25. Kg1 Qb1+
26. Kf2 Qc2+ 27. Kg1 Qb1+ {1/2-1/2 Bacrot -Sutovsky, Khanty-Mansiysk 2005.}) ({
Playing against the c5-pawn does not question Black's stability on dark
squares.} 16. Ba3 b6 17. Bb4 {This is spectacular but the bishop's exchange
just increases Black's stability on dark squares.} ({True, he does not face
major problems after} 17. Bb5 Qd6 18. Bc6 Bf5 {either.}) 17... Bxb4 18. cxb4
Qd6 19. Rbc1 Bf5 20. bxc5 bxc5 $11 {and Black had little to complain about in
Yevseev-Avrukh, Groningen 1996.}) (16. Rb5 {does not create any threat and is
best met with a developing move such as the untested yet} Re8 $146) 16... Rb8 {
Freeing the bishop from the task of defending b7 but also sustaining ...b7-b5
under certain circumstances.} (16... b6 {achieves only the former, but was
tried in numerous games, too.}) 17. Ba3 {Now that the enemy queen does not
have the blocking square on d6 anymore this makes more sense than one move
earlier. White has tried a wide range of alternatives:} ({The exchange
sacrifice prepared by} 17. Rb5 $5 {does not look entirely sound as it does not
help activating the c1-bishop:} Bd7 18. Rxa5 Qxa5 19. f5 c4 20. f6 Qc5+ 21. Kh1
Kh8 22. Qh6 Rg8 {Black has parried all the immediate threats retaining his
material advantage, Bormida-Peto,P IECG 2001/Telechess.}) (17. g4 $5 {runs into
} b5 {since the g4-pawn is hanging.} 18. Bb2 Qh4 19. f5 Bb7 20. Qf4 c4 {
The b2-bishop is still very passive and White's king is in bigger danger than
Black's.} 21. Bf3 g5 $17 {Black has stabilized the position retaining the
better structure, G. Kovacs -Y. Vovk,Szombathely 2008.}) ({Increasing the
pressure against b7 fails to yield the desired effect as Black can develop his
bishop anyway.} 17. Bf3 Bf5 18. Rb5 ({The point is that after} 18. Rxb7 Rxb7
19. Bxb7 Qf6 {Black's counterplay is too strong for instance 20.Bb2 c4 or} 20.
Ba3 Bxc3 21. Qd5 Be6 22. Qc6 Qd4+ 23. Kh1 Bb4 $17 {White is poorly coordinated
and his king's position is weak, Kraus)-Doros, Pardubice 2012.}) 18... b6 19.
Ba3 Rc8 {Overdefending c5. White's attack has reached a dead end and he
decided forcing a draw by repetition.} 20. Bb7 Rc7 21. Bd5 Rc8 (21... Rd7 {
allows the exchange sacrifice for a pawn, but it should not yield more than
equality anway.} 22. Rxa5 Rxd6 23. c4 bxa5 24. Bxc5 Be6 $11) 22. Bb7 Rc7 23.
Bd5 Rc8 {1/2-1/2 Nolte-Nguyen, Ho Chi Minh City 2009.}) (17. Bb2 {fails to
activate the bishop:} b5 {Another case when ...Rb8 proves more useful than ...
b7-b6.} 18. Rbd1 Bd7 19. Bf3 c4 20. Kh1 Bf5 {Now that Black has taken the
control overthe d3-square he can place his bishop more actively without
fearing g2-g4.} 21. Qd4 Bb6 22. Qd5 Be6 23. Qe5 Qd7 24. Ba3 Rfe8 {with
comfortable play Pelletier-Caruana, Biel 2011}) 17... Bf5 18. Rbd1 {The most
natural move, over defending White's main trump, the passed pawn.} (18. Rb5 {
is once again ineffective:} a6 19. Rxc5 Bb6 20. Kh1 Bxc5 21. Bxc5 Qd7 22. Bb6
Be4 {It becomes clear that only White can have problems along the long
diagonal.} 23. Qd4 Rbe8 24. Bd1 {In Gajewski-Sutovsky, Rijeka 2010 Black
missed a good opportunity to take over the initiative with} Re6 25. Bc7 Qc6 26.
Qd2 Rd8 $1 $17 27. Bxd8 Rxd6 {but went on winning anyway.}) (18. Rbc1 {is a
super-refined move, over defending c3, but it does not make much of a
difference with respect to the familiar patterns.} Rc8 19. g4 Bd7 20. Bf3 b5
21. f5 Qh4 22. Rce1 {The rook belongs in the centre, of course.} Qf6 {but now
the c3-pawn needs defending.} 23. Bb2 c4 24. fxg6 hxg6 25. Re7 Bb6+ 26. Kg2 Be6
$11 {Alpert-Nemec, ICCF Email 2001.}) 18... Rc8 {A well timed switch to the
c-file. The idea is similar with that behind ...Ra8-b8: Black not only defends
the pawn but also sustains its advance.} 19. g4 {The only challenging move.} ({
The neutral} 19. Bf3 {allows Black becoming active:} Qf6 20. d7 ({The passive} 
20. Bb2 $6 {leads to trouble after} c4 21. Rfe1 Bd3 $17 {Belov-Nikolenko,
Moscow 2000.}) 20... Rcd8 21. Bxc5 Rxd7 $11 {with comfortable equality as in a
couple of correspondence games.}) 19... Bd7 {Of course, Black should not allow
d6-d7.} 20. f5 Qh4 {Black has lost time with his bishop but got
counterattacking ideas in exchange.} 21. Bf3 {According to Krasenkov, in
Krasenkow-Avrukh, Izmir 2004 Black should have continued with} b5 {Indeed,
this is the most consequent plan, leaving the position uncertain.} *

