1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8.
h3 {White intends developing his bishops in natural ways without being forced
to advance any of his central pawns after ...Bg4. The plan sounds logical but
implies delaying the development.} O-O (8... Qa5 9. Bd2 {would transpose to
Line 4 with an important extra tempo for White, h2-h3.}) 9. Be3 Nc6 10. Be2
cxd4 11. cxd4 {If allowed completing his development White will retain a small
plus, but Black can use the extra tempo to break the centre immediately.} f5
12. Bc4+ {White tries making use of the weakened diagonal} ({The alternative is
} 12. Qb3+ Kh8 13. Rd1 (13. exf5 {offers Black a stable position and excelent
play after} Qa5+ 14. Bd2 Qxf5 15. Qe3 Be6 16. O-O Rad8 17. Bc3 Bd5 $11 {
Mikanovic-Turov, Quebec 2001.}) 13... fxe4 14. Ng5 ({Engines recommend} 14. Ne5
Nxe5 15. dxe5 Qa5+ 16. Rd2 Qxe5 {"with equality" but Black is two pawns up
after all.}) 14... Nxd4 {For the sake of centralization Black ignores the
threat on f7.} 15. Qc4 (15. Nf7+ Rxf7 16. Qxf7 Be6 17. Qf4 Qa5+ 18. Bd2 Qxa2
$19 {offers Black a decisive counterattack and a couple of pawns for the
exchange..}) ({One important point is that} 15. Bxd4 {does not force Black
staying in a pin as he has} Qa5+ 16. Kf1 Qxg5 $17 {(Krasenkow).}) 15... Qa5+ {
White had nothing to show for his missing pawns and the king's delay in the
centre, Arencibia Rodriguez-Eljanov, Ubeda 2001.}) (12. exf5 {can be answered
with the familiar} Qa5+ 13. Bd2 Qxf5 14. Bc3 Be6 {[%csl Gd5]} 15. O-O Rad8 $11
{[%csl Rd4] Black has perfect development and a good control over d5, at least
compensating for the kingside weaknesses, Korobov -Goloshchapov, Ordzhonikidze
2001}) 12... Kh8 13. O-O (13. e5 {gives up the control over d5 in the hope of
turning the g7-bishop into a passive piece.} f4 14. Bc1 b5 ({This is a better
way of fighting against the bishop than} 14... Na5 {when White has} 15. Bd3 {
preparing either h3-h4-h5 or simply Be4 fighting for the d5-square.} Be6 16. h4
$14 {Belov-Timofeev, Serpukhov 2008.}) 15. Be2 ({Or if} 15. Bb3 Na5 16. Bc2 Bb7
{with a favourable version of the aforementioned game since Black will soon
get counterplay along the c-file.}) 15... Be6 $11 {with normal play.}) 13... f4
{This is a double edged move. Black wins a pawn but conceals White the stable
f3-square for his pieces turning the f4-pawn into a potential weakness.
Practice has shown that White has compensation for the pawn but this should
reach for a draw only.} 14. Bd2 Nxd4 15. Bc3 Nxf3+ 16. Qxf3 Qc7 17. Rac1 Bd7
18. Bxg7+ Kxg7 19. Bb5 Bc6 20. Bxc6 bxc6 21. Rc5 Rac8 22. Rfc1 Qd6 *

