1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8.
Bb5+ {With this early check in the spirit of the Bogoindian White intends
reducing Black's pressure on d4. This may happen if he either interfers the
d-file with ...Bd7 or ...Nd7 or, like in our line, by placing the knight under
the bishop's attack (and at least temporarily under a pin).} Nc6 {This is the
most active continuation. In order to reduce Black's pressure on d4 White will
most likely have to give up his bishop.} 9. O-O {This is the old main line,
once supposed to offer White a symbolic advantage but now rather inoffensive.}
({For the more resolute} 9. d5 {see line 10.}) 9... O-O 10. Be3 ({Preventing ..
.Bg4 wastes too much time to bother Black:} 10. h3 cxd4 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. cxd4
Ba6 13. Re1 c5 $11 {with comfortable equality if not more.}) ({This is not a
good moment for gaining space:} 10. d5 Bxc3 11. Bh6 Nd4 {Black has gabbed a
pawn without being forced to misplace his knight, which is doing quite all
right in the centre.} 12. Nxd4 Bxd4 13. Bxf8 Qxf8 14. Rb1 a6 15. Be2 b5 $15 {
with overwhelming compensation for the exchange, Gerzhoy-So, Montreal 2012.})
10... Bg4 {It is better to delay the exchange on d4, since otherwise after
Bxc6 the c6-pawn will be exposed along the half open c-file.} 11. Bxc6 ({
Once again} 11. d5 {offersBlack comfortable play:} Ne5 12. Be2 (12. Bxc5 Nxf3+
13. gxf3 Bh3 14. Re1 Bxc3 $17 {wins an exchange at no cost.}) 12... Nxf3+ 13.
Bxf3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Bxc3 15. Rab1 b6 16. Bxc5 Be5 {Drawn Schenk-Bromberger,
Augsburg 2002.}) (11. dxc5 {offers Black a comfortable choice.} Qc7 $5 ({
Actually there is nothing wrong with retrieving the pawn at once.} 11... Bxc3
12. Rc1 Bg7) 12. Bxc6 ({Sticking to the extra pawn with} 12. Rc1 {offers Black
the initiative after} Rfd8 13. Qe2 Ne5 $15) 12... Qxc6 13. Qc2 Bxf3 14. gxf3 b6
{A typical move with the actual queenside structure. Black opens the c- and
a-file for his major pieces turning a2 and c3 into weaknesses.} ({Black can
also look for counterplay on the opposite wing with} 14... f5 $11 {Xu,Jun-Wang,
Y Ningbo 2011.}) 15. cxb6 axb6 {The mutual queenside weaknesses as well as the
exposed white king make a draw quite probable, Lou,Y-Wei,Y China 2015.}) 11...
bxc6 12. Rc1 Qa5 13. Qe2 Rfd8 {Black has completed his development
harmoniously and his position is preferable already.} 14. Rfd1 $6 {Careless.} (
14. e5 {was somewhat better but Black's position remains very pleasant after,
say,} Be6 {or 14...Qb5, with excellent play on light squares.}) 14... Bxf3 15.
gxf3 ({Probably missing the trick but} 15. Qxf3 Qxa2 $17 {is not a dream for
White either.}) 15... cxd4 16. cxd4 Bxd4 17. Bxd4 (17. Rxc6 {may be a lesser
evil:} Bxe3 18. Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. Qxe3 ({But not} 19. fxe3 Rd2 $19 {followed by
either ...Qg5+ or ...Qxa2.}) 19... Qxa2 $15) 17... Rxd4 18. Rxd4 Qg5+ 19. Kf1
Qxc1+ {With an extra pawn and good winning chances, M. Ivanov-Khalifman, Minsk
2012.} *

