1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8.
Bb5+ Nc6 9. d5 {Following the Anand-Gelfand match this resolute move has
enjoyed some popularity.} Qa5 (9... a6 {is the main alternative. White's best
is} 10. Be2 $5 {transposing to a position from the 8.Be2 line with the
difference that Black has weakened the b6-square, which slightly favours White
even though things remain unclear.} Bxc3+ 11. Bd2 Bxa1 12. Qxa1 Nd4 13. Nxd4
cxd4 14. Qxd4 f6) 10. Rb1 Bxc3+ {This is the simplest way out of the complex
queenside tension.} ({After} 10... a6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. O-O Qxa2 {Anand
unleashed the novelty} 13. Rb2 {yielding him some initiative after} Qa5 14. d6
{Anand -Gelfand, Moscow 2012.}) 11. Bd2 a6 12. Bxc6+ {The only principled move.
} ({If} 12. Be2 Nd4 {We reach a familiar situation, where Black does not have
passive pieces in exchange for his pawn.}) ({Or if} 12. Ba4 {as in
Privitera-Kaufman, Budapest 2010 Black has} Bxd2+ 13. Nxd2 b5 14. dxc6 bxa4 $15
) 12... bxc6 13. dxc6 Be6 {Pawns are equal and Black's free development is not
marred by the c6-pawn too much.} 14. Rc1 Bxd2+ 15. Qxd2 Qb4 $1 {it is
important to keep the tension preventing the activation of the white king.} ({
In a later game Black played less accurately:} 15... Qxd2+ 16. Kxd2 O-O-O+ 17.
Ke3 c4 18. Nd4 {with some light initiative in Cmilyte-Tate, Caleta 2014.}) 16.
O-O (16. Qxb4 cxb4 {offers Black a dangerous queenside majority. The immediate
threats are ...Bxa2 and ...0-0-0 so White should make use of the dynamic
resources yielded by the far advanced pawn.} 17. c7 Kd7 18. Ke2 Ra7 19. Ne5+
Kc8 20. Nc6 Rxc7 21. Nxb4 Bc4+ 22. Ke3 a5 $11) 16... Qxd2 17. Nxd2 O-O-O 18.
Nb3 {The only way to avoid losing the c6-pawn.} ({For instance:} 18. Rc2 Kc7) (
{or} 18. Nf3 c4 19. Ng5 Rd4 20. Rc2 Rhd8 {Delaying White's rook doubling by a
decisive tempo.} 21. f3 R8d6 $17 {Black will win the c-pawn and keep his.})
18... Bxb3 19. axb3 Rd3 {The draw becomes quite obvious now.} 20. Rxc5 Rxb3 21.
Ra5 Rb6 22. Rfa1 Rd8 23. h3 Rxc6 24. Rxa6 Rxa6 25. Rxa6 {and the game was
drawn after 8 more unnecessary moves, Sasikiran-Grischuk, Eilat 2012.} *

